'\n| ''11''<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Tenjimbashisuji Rokuchome Station|Tenjimbashisuji Rokuch\u014dme Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Hankyu Kyoto Main Line]]''\n| \u962a\u6025\u4eac\u90fd\u672c\u7dda\n| ''1969''<ref group=\"Note\">Between [[Awaji Station]] and [[Kawaramachi Station (Kyoto)|Kawaramachi Station]]</ref>\n| \u2013\n| ''{{convert|41.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}''\n| ''22''<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Awaji Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[File:Osaka Metro Sakaisuji line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 6\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Sakaisuji Line]]\n| \u583a\u7b4b\u7dda\n| 1969\n| 1993\n| {{convert|8.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 10\n|-\n| style=\"background:#a9cc51\" | Lime\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 7\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]]\n| \u9577\u5800\u9db4\u898b\u7dd1\u5730\u7dda\n| 1990\n| 1997\n| {{convert|15.0|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 17\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ee7b1a\" | Orange\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Imazatosuji line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 8\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Imazatosuji Line]]\n| \u4eca\u91cc\u7b4b\u7dda \n| 2006\n| \u2013\n| {{convert|11.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 11\n|-\n| colspan=7 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''TOTAL (Subway only \u2013 not incl. ''trackage rights'' portions):'''\n| '''{{convert|129.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}'''\n| '''123'''\n|-\n! colspan=9 | [[People mover|Automated people mover]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2 style=\"background:#00a0de\" | Light <br> blue\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[File:Osaka Metro Nanko Port Town line symbol.svg|22px]]\n| rowspan=2 | New Tram\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Nank\u014d Port Town Line]]\n| rowspan=2 | \u5357\u6e2f\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\u30bf\u30a6\u30f3\u7dda\n| 1997<ref group=\"Note\">Owned by Osaka Port Transport System between [[Cosmosquare Station]] and [[Trade Center-mae Station]]</ref>\n| \u2013\n| {{convert|0.7|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 1<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Trade Center-mae Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| 1981<ref group=\"Note\">Between [[Trade Center-mae Station]] and [[Suminoekoen Station]]</ref>\n| 2005\n| {{convert|7.2|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 9\n|-\n| colspan=7 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''TOTAL (Subway, incl. People Mover):'''\n| '''{{convert|137.8|km|mi|abbr=on}}'''<ref name=\"overview\" />\n| '''133'''<ref name=\"overview\" />\n|}\n\n;Table notes\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n===Planned line and extensions===\n\nIn addition, there are five line extensions and one new line that are planned. However, on August 28, 2014, the [[Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau]] met about creating the extensions of the later five of the six lines listed below, and have stated considering the current cost of the new extensions (and the possibly of privatization at the time), the government has also considered using [[light rail transit]] or [[bus rapid transit]] instead.<ref name=\"\u5730\u4e0b\u9244\uff14\u7dda\u5ef6\u4f38\">{{cite news | url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/local/osaka/news/20140829-OYTNT50036.html | script-title=ja:\u5730\u4e0b\u9244\uff14\u7dda\u5ef6\u4f38\u300c\u63a1\u7b97\u53b3\u3057\u3044\u300d\u3000\u6709\u8b58\u8005\u5be9\u8b70\u4f1a | work=[[Yomiuri Online]] | language=Japanese | date=August 29, 2014 | accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref> Osaka Metro is now experimenting with bus rapid transit on the route of the Imazatosuji Line extension, with \u201cImazato Liner\u201d service between Imazato and Yuzato-Rokuch\u014dme slated to begin in April 2019.\n\nWith Osaka being the host of [[Expo 2025]], there are also plans to extend the Chuo Line northwest onto Yume-shima (the event's planned site), with a terminus on Sakura-jima north of [[Universal Studios Japan]]. Provisions were put in place for such an extension when the existing road tunnel between Cosmosquare and Yume-shima was built, but the current state of the artificial island (with only industrial facilities and a lone convenience store for workers) meant it would have been unlikely to proceed had Osaka lost its bid.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Line <br />color\n! Mark\n! Line <br />number\n! Name\n! Start\n! Terminus\n! Length\n|-\n| style=\"background:#0078BE; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Yotsubashi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Yotsubashi Line]]\n| [[Nishi-Umeda Station|Nishi-Umeda]]\n| [[J\u016bs\u014d Station|J\u016bs\u014d]], later towards [[Shin-\u014csaka Station|Shin-\u014csaka]]\n| 2.9&nbsp;km (to J\u016bs\u014d)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#019A66; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Chuo line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 4\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]]\n| {{STN|Cosmosquare}}\n| Yumeshima\n| ''(TBD)''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#E44D93; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Sennichimae line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 5\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Sennichimae Line]]\n| [[Minami-Tatsumi Station|Minami-Tatsumi]]\n| towards [[Mito Station (Osaka)|Mito]]\n| ''(TBD)''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#A9CC51; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 7\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]]\n| [[Taish\u014d Station (Osaka)|Taish\u014d]]\n| Tsurumachi Yonch\u014dme (vicinity)\n| 5.5&nbsp;km\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EE7B1A; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Imazatosuji line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 8\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Imazatosuji Line]]\n| [[Imazato Station (Osaka Municipal Subway)|Imazato]]\n| Yuzato Rokuch\u014dme\n| 6.7&nbsp;km\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFE0\"\n| ''(TBD)''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | -\n| [[Osaka Municipal Subway Line 9|Line 9]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Shikitsu\u2013Nagayoshi Line ''(provisional)''\n| [[Suminoek\u014den Station|Suminoek\u014den]]\n| [[Kire-Uriwari Station|Kire-Uriwari]]\n| 6.9&nbsp;km\n|}\n\n== Technology and rolling stock ==\nOsaka Municipal Subway [[rolling stock]] use two types of [[traction motor|propulsion systems]]. The vast majority of lines use trains with conventional [[electric motor]]s, but the two newest lines, the [[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]] and [[Imazatosuji Line]], use [[linear motor]]-powered trains, which allow them to use smaller trains and tunnels, reducing construction costs. These two lines have half-height [[automatic platform gates]] installed at all station platforms, as does the Sennichimae Line.<ref name=\"Sennichimae Line doors\">{{cite web | url=http://www.apt-newschannel.com/id/berita-berita/taiwan/detail/osaka-subways-sennichimae-line-to-have-platform-s/ | title=Osaka subway's Sennichimae Line to have platform screen doors installed in every station Chinese translation to follow | work=Asian Public Transport | date=February 13, 2014 | accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlso, unlike other rapid transit networks in Japan, most Osaka subway lines use a [[third rail]] electrification system for trains. Only three lines use [[overhead catenary]]: the Sakaisuji Line, to accommodate through services on Hankyu trackage; and the linear-motor Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi and Imazatosuji Lines. Also unusually, all lines use [[standard gauge]]; there are no [[narrow gauge]] sections of track due to the network being almost entirely self-enclosed.\n\n===Electric motored===\n* 10 series: [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]]\n* 20 series: [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]]\n* 21 series (\"[[Osaka Municipal Subway New 20 series|New 20 series]]\"): [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]]\n* 22 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Tanimachi Line]]\n* 23 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Yotsubashi Line]]\n* 24 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]] (A variant of the 24 series is used on the Ch\u016b\u014d Line in Osaka Port Transport System livery.)\n* 25 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Sennichimae Line]]\n* 66 series: [[Sakaisuji Line]]\n* [[Osaka Municipal Subway 30000 series|30000 series]]: [[Tanimachi Line]] and [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]]\n\n===Linear motored===\n* [[Osaka Municipal Subway 70 series|70 series]]: [[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]]\n* 80 series: [[Imazatosuji Line]]\n\n==Fares==\n[[File:Shinsaibashi Station 4.JPG|thumb|Ticket machines and fare maps at Shinsaibashi Station]]\nOsaka Metro charges five types of fares for single rides, based on the distance traveled in each journey.<ref name=\"tickets\">{{cite web |url=http://www.osakametro.co.jp/foreign/english/Fares.html |title=Tickets |publisher=Osaka Metro |date= |accessdate=April 14, 2018}}</ref> Some discount fares exist.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n! width=80px | Distance travelled\n! style=\"width:150px;\" | Rates (yen)<ref name=\"tickets\" />\n|-\n!width=80px|1\u20133&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 180 yen\n*children: 90 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|4\u20137&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 230 yen\n*children: 120 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|8\u201313&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 280 yen\n*children: 140 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|14\u201319&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 320 yen\n*children: 160 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|20\u201325&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 370 yen\n*children: 190 yen\n|}\n\n==Incidents==\nOn April 8, 1970, a gas explosion occurred during the construction of the [[Tanimachi Line]] at [[Tenjimbashisuji Rokuch\u014dme Station]], killing 79 people and injuring 420.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u5e02\u4f1a\u306e\u3042\u3086\u307f|url=http://www.city.osaka.lg.jp/shikai/page/0000001377.html|website=Osaka City Council Website|ref=\u5e02\u4f1a\u306e\u3042\u3086\u307f|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pulvers|first=Roger|title=Beware the parallels between boom-time Japan and present-day China|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2012/11/04/commentary/beware-the-parallels-between-boom-time-japan-and-present-day-china/#.U94OYRbOP-k|work=[[The Japan Times]]|ref=Parallels|date=November 4, 2012|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref> The gas leaked out from a detached joint and filled the tunnel and exploded, creating a fire pillar of over 10 meters and destroying 495 houses and buildings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gas Explosion at a Subway Construction Site|url=http://www.sozogaku.com/fkd/en/cfen/CB1012037.html|publisher=Failure Knowledge Center|ref=Case Details|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transport in Keihanshin]]\n* [[List of Osaka Metro stations]]\n* [[List of metro systems]]\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|\u014csaka Metro}}\n* [http://www.osakametro.co.jp/foreign/english/index.html Osaka Metro official site (English)]\n* [http://www.osakametro.co.jp/library/english/img/map.pdf Osaka Metro route map (PDF)]\n\n{{Metro systems in Japan}}\n{{Osaka transit}}\n\n[[Category:Osaka Municipal Subway|*]]\n[[Category:Underground rapid transit in Japan]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:1500 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Japanese transit company from Keihanshin}}\n{{Infobox Public transit\n| name             = Osaka Metro\n| image            = Osaka Metro logo.svg\n| imagesize        = 100px\n| image2           = OsakaCity10 1121F and 21 21603F.jpg\n| imagesize2       = 300px\n| image3           = OsakaSubway-32608F.JPG\n| imagesize3       = 300px\n| caption3         = '''Top:''' 10 series and 21 series trains on the Mid\u014dsuji Line. <br> '''Bottom:''' A 30000 series train on the Tanimachi Line.\n| native_name      = \u5927\u962a\u30e1\u30c8\u30ed{{efn|The official name of the network in Japanese is still written as '''Osaka Metro'''.|name=metroname}}\n| owner            = [[#Management|Osaka Metro Co., Ltd]]\n| locale           = [[Keihanshin|Keihanshin region]], [[Japan]]\n| transit_type     = [[Tram]] (''[[de jure]]'')<ref name=\"tetsuyou\">{{Cite book|author=[[Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport (Japan)|Kokudo K\u014dts\u016b Sh\u014d]] Tetsud\u014d Kyoku|title=Tetsud\u014d Y\u014dran (Heisei 17 Nendo)|year=2005|language=Japanese|publisher=Denkisha Kenky\u016bkai|location=Tokyo|isbn=4-88548-106-6|page=228}}\n</ref><br>[[Rapid transit|Metro]]; [[Automated guideway transit|AGT]] (''[[de facto]]'')\n| lines            = 8 (+ 1 People Mover)\n| stations         = [[List of Osaka Metro stations|123]]<ref name=\"overview\" /><br />133 (incl. People Mover)<ref name=\"overview\" />\n| ridership        = 2,464,000 (FY2013)<ref name=\"balance_sheet\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kotsu.city.osaka.lg.jp/business/management/financial/yosan_kessan.html |title=\u4ea4\u901a\u5c40\u306e\u4e88\u7b97\u30fb\u6c7a\u7b97\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 |publisher=\u5927\u962a\u5e02\u55b6\u4ea4\u901a\u5c40 [Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau] |language=Japanese |trans-title=For budget and balance sheet of Transportation Bureau |date= |accessdate=December 18, 2014}}</ref>\n| annual_ridership = \n| operator         = [[Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau]] (1933\u2013March 31, 2018) <br> Osaka Municipal Rapid Electric Tramway, K.K. (April 1, 2018\u2013present; 100% owned by the Osaka Municipal Government)\n| began_operation  = May 20, 1933\n| vehicles         = \n| system_length    = {{Convert|129.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"overview\" /><br />{{Convert|137.8|km|mi|abbr=on}} (incl. <br />People Mover)<ref name=\"overview\" />\n| track_gauge      = {{Track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| average_speed    = \n| top_speed        = {{Convert|70|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n| el               = Third rail lines: 750 V DC, [[third rail]]<br />Sakaisuji Line and linear motor metro lines: 1,500 V DC, [[overhead line]]s\n| map              = [[File:Wide-Area Map of Osaka City Subway.png|300px]]\n| map_state        = show\n}}\n\nThe {{nihongo|'''Osaka Metro'''|\u5927\u962a\u30e1\u30c8\u30ed{{efn|name=metroname}}|\u014csaka Metoro}} is a major [[rapid transit system]] in the [[Osaka Metropolitan Area]] of [[Japan]]. It serves the city of [[Osaka]] and the adjacent municipalities of [[Higashi\u014dsaka, Osaka|Higashiosaka]], [[Kadoma, Osaka|Kadoma]], [[Moriguchi, Osaka|Moriguchi]], [[Sakai, Osaka|Sakai]], [[Suita, Osaka|Suita]], and [[Yao, Osaka|Yao]]. Osaka Metro forms an [[Transport in Greater Osaka|integral part]] of the extensive mass transit system of Greater Osaka (part of the [[Kansai]] region), having [[List of Osaka Metro stations|123]]<ref name=\"overview\" /> out of the 1,108 rail stations (2007) in the [[Osaka-Kobe-Kyoto]] region.<ref>[http://www.misol.ne.jp/information/option_datalist.htm MiSoL ASP\u4f1a\u54e1\u30b5\u30fc\u30d3\u30b9\u30fb\u30a2\u30d7\u30ea\u30b1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u6982\u8981<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027074625/http://www.misol.ne.jp/information/option_datalist.htm |date=2007-10-27 }}</ref> In 2010, the greater Osaka region had 13 million rail passengers daily (see [[Transport in Keihanshin]]) of which the Osaka Municipal Subway (as it was then known) accounted for 2.29 million.<ref>http://www.mlit.go.jp/kisha/kisha07/01/010330_3/01.pdf</ref>\n\nOsaka Metro is the only subway system in Japan to be [[Rail transport in Japan#Railway and tram|legally classified]] as a [[tram]]way, whereas all other subway systems in Japan are legally classified as [[railway]]s. Despite this, it has characteristics typical of a full-fledged metro system.<ref name=\"tetsuyou\"/>\n\n==Overview==\nThe network's first service, the [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]] from {{STN|Umeda}} to {{STN|Shinsaibashi}}, opened in 1933.<ref name=\"railfan576\">{{cite magazine |author= |date=April 2009 |title=\u516c\u55b6\u5730\u4e0b\u9244\u5728\u7c4d\u8eca\u6570\u30d3\u30c3\u30b0\uff13\u3000\u5927\u962a\u5e02\u4ea4\u901a\u5c40 (One of the big three public subway operators: Osaka Municipal Subway)|magazine=[[Japan Railfan Magazine]] |volume=49 |issue=576 |pages=88\u201399}}</ref> As a north-south [[trunk route]], it is the oldest and busiest line in the whole network.<ref name=\"most crowded train lines Osaka\">{{cite news | url=http://en.rocketnews24.com/2014/09/07/the-most-crowded-train-lines-during-rush-hour-in-tokyo-osaka-and-nagoya-are/ | title=The most crowded train lines during rush hour in Tokyo, Osaka, and Nagoya are\u2026 | work=Rocket News 24 | last=Rogers|first=Krista | accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"\u5927\u962a\u5e9c\u5185\u3067\u50cd\u304f\u4eba\u306e\u901a\u52e4\u6642\u9593\">{{cite news | url=http://bizmakoto.jp/makoto/articles/1409/04/news100.html | script-title=ja:\u5927\u962a\u5e9c\u5185\u3067\u50cd\u304f\u4eba\u306e\u901a\u52e4\u6642\u9593\u306f\u300c52\u5206\u300d\u2015\u2015\u7406\u60f3\u306e\u8def\u7dda\u306f\uff1f | website=bizmakoto.jp | language=Japanese | date=September 9, 2014 | accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=overview /> Both it and the main east-west route, the [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]], were later extended to the north and east, respectively. These extensions are owned by other railway companies, but both Osaka Metro and these private operators run their own set of trains [[through train|through between the two sections]].\n\nAll but one of the remaining lines of the network, including the [[Yotsubashi Line]], [[Tanimachi Line]], and [[Sennichimae Line]], are completely independent lines with no through services. The lone exception is the [[Sakaisuji Line]], which operates through trains to existing [[Hankyu Railway]] lines and is the only line to operate through services to existing railway lines that are not isolated from the [[suburban rail|national rail network]] (which is the case with the Mid\u014dsuji and Ch\u016b\u014d Lines).\n\nNearly all stations have a [[letter number combination]], the letter identifying the line served by the station and the number indicating the relative location of the station on the line. For example, Higobashi Station on the Yotsubashi Line is also known as Y12. This combination is heard in bilingual Japanese-English automated next-station announcements on board all trains, which also provide information on local businesses near the station. Only Hankyu stations served by the Sakaisuji Line do not follow this convention.\n\n===Management===\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Osaka Metro Co., Ltd\n| trade_name = Osaka Metro\n| native_name = [[w:ja:\u5927\u962a\u5e02\u9ad8\u901f\u96fb\u6c17\u8ecc\u9053|\u5927\u962a\u5e02\u9ad8\u901f\u96fb\u6c17\u8ecc\u9053]]\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| romanized_name = \u014csaka-shi K\u014dsoku Denki Kid\u014d kabushiki gaisha<br>lit. \"Osaka Municipal Rapid Electric Tramway Share Company\"\n| logo = Osaka Metro logo 3.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| image = Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau Main office.jpg\n| image_caption = Headquarters\n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]] ([[municipally owned corporation|municipally owned]]) [[kabushiki gaisha|KK]]\n| industry = [[Transportation industry|Transportation]]\n| predecessor = [[Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2017|06|01}} (incorporation)<br>{{start date and age|2018|04|01}} (effective corporatization of Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau)\n| founder = [[Osaka]] Municipal Government\n| hq_location_city = [[Nishi-ku, Osaka]]\n| hq_location_country = Japan\n| area_served = [[Keihanshin]]\n| key_people = \n| products = \n| owner = [[Osaka]] Municipal Government (100%)\n| subsid = [[w:ja:\u5927\u962a\u30b7\u30c6\u30a3\u30d0\u30b9|Osaka City Bus Corporation]]\n| num_employees = 4,936\n| num_employees_year = 2019\n| website = {{URL|www.osakametro.co.jp}}\n}}\n\nThe network is operated by a [[municipally owned corporation|municipally owned]] [[kabushiki gaisha|stock company]] trading as the '''Osaka Metro Co., Ltd'''.{{efn|in Japanese: {{nihongo||\u5927\u962a\u5e02\u9ad8\u901f\u96fb\u6c17\u8ecc\u9053\u682a\u5f0f\u4f1a\u793e|\u014csaka-shi K\u014dsoku Denki Kid\u014d kabushiki gaisha|lit. \"Osaka Municipal Rapid Electric Tramway Share Company\"}}}} Until March 31, 2018, the network was operated by the [[Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau]] as {{nihongo|'''Osaka Municipal Subway'''|\u5927\u962a\u5e02\u55b6\u5730\u4e0b\u9244|\u014csaka-shiei chikatetsu}}, and was the oldest publicly operated subway network in Japan, having begun operations in 1933. A proposal to [[corporatization|corporatize]] the Osaka subway was sent to the city government in February 2013 and was given final approval in 2017. The rationale behind corporatization is that it would bring private investors to Osaka and could help revive Osaka's economy. The new operator was incorporated in June 1, 2017, and took over operations on April 1, 2018.\n\nThe Osaka Metro Company also operates all city buses in Osaka, through its majority-owned subsidiary, the [[w:ja:\u5927\u962a\u30b7\u30c6\u30a3\u30d0\u30b9|Osaka City Bus Corporation]].\n\n==Branding==\nOsaka Metro stations are denoted by a white-on-dark-blue icon placed at ground-level entrances, depicting an \"M\" (for \"Metro\") based on a coiled ribbon, which would form an \"O\" (for \"Osaka\") when viewed from the side, with the \"Osaka Metro\" [[wordmark]] set in [[Gotham (typeface)|Gotham]]. \"Osaka Metro\" (in Latin characters) is the official branding in Japanese, and is always represented as such in official media. (News outlets have been seen to use \u5927\u962a\u30e1\u30c8\u30ed, presumably to better flow with article text.) Individual lines are represented by a public-facing name (e.g. \u201cMid\u014dsuji Line\u201d for Line No. 1) and a specific color, as well as a single Latin letter, which is paired with a different number at each station for easy identification (see below). Icons for each line (featured in station wayfinding signage) are represented by a solid [[roundel]] in the line color, superimposed with the line's letter-designation in [[Parisine]].\n\n[[File:OMTB_logomark.svg|left|thumb|150px|''Mio-Den'']]\n\nAn older branding (also used on the [[tram]] network run by the city until 1969) is the \"Mio-Den\" mark, which depicts an old-fashioned {{nihongo|depth-marker, [[File:Emblem_of_Osaka,_Osaka.svg|16px]]|\u6faa\u6a19|mio-tsukushi}}, the logo for [[Osaka]] City, over the [[kanji]] for {{nihongo|electricity|\u96fb|den}}, short for {{nihongo|\u201celectric train\u201d|\u96fb\u8eca|densha}}. This mark is still present on newer trainsets and staff uniforms as a connection to the subway network's roots.\n\n[[File:Osaka_Metro_Logo.svg|left|thumb|150px|''Maruko'']]\n\nWhen it was run by the [[Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau]], the subway used a logo known as the {{nihongo|\u201cCircle-Ko\u201d|\u30de\u30eb\u30b3|Maru-Ko}} symbol, which is a katakana {{nihongo|\u201cko\u201d|\u30b3}} for {{nihongo|\u201ctransport\u201d|\u4ea4\u901a|k\u014dts\u016b}} superimposed over a circular capital \u201cO\u201d for \u201cOsaka\u201d (see infobox, above). This remains on many trainsets and at stations, but is slated for replacement with the Osaka Metro logo as the changeover progresses.\n\n==Lines==\nCurrently, there are eight lines, operating on {{convert|129.9|km|mi|sp=us}} and serving 123 stations; there is also a {{convert|7.9|km|mi|adj=on|sp=us}}-long, 10-station [[People mover|automated people mover]] line known as the \"New Tram\".<ref name=\"overview\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kotsu.city.osaka.lg.jp/enjoy/web_museum/subway/business.html |script-title=ja:\u55b6\u696d\u7dda\u306e\u6982\u8981 |publisher=\u5927\u962a\u5e02\u55b6\u4ea4\u901a\u5c40 [Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau] |language=Japanese |trans-title=Overview of operating lines |date= |accessdate=June 7, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140111193102/http://www.kotsu.city.osaka.lg.jp/enjoy/web_museum/subway/business.html |archivedate=January 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Line <br />color\n! Mark\n! Line <br />number\n! Name\n! Japanese\n! Opened\n! Last extension\n! Length<ref name=\"overview\" />\n! Stations<ref name=\"overview\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=2 style=\"background:#e5171f; color:white;\" | Red\n| rowspan=2  style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Midosuji line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| ''Via trackage rights''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Kita-Osaka Kyuko Railway|Kitaky\u016b Namboku Line]]''\n| \u5317\u5927\u962a\u6025\u884c\u96fb\u9244\n| ''1970''\n| ''1970''\n| ''{{convert|5.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}''\n| ''4''<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Esaka Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| Line 1\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]]\n| \u5fa1\u5802\u7b4b\u7dda\n| 1933\n| 1987\n| {{convert|24.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 20\n|-\n| style=\"background:#522886; color:white;\" | Purple\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Tanimachi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 2\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Tanimachi Line]]\n| \u8c37\u753a\u7dda\n| 1967\n| 1983\n| {{convert|28.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 26\n|-\n| style=\"background:#0078be; color:white;\" | Blue\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Yotsubashi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Yotsubashi Line]]\n| \u56db\u3064\u6a4b\u7dda\n| 1942\n| 1972\n| {{convert|11.4|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 11\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"background:#019a66; color:white;\" | Green\n| rowspan=3  style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Chuo line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| rowspan=2 | Line 4\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]] (''[[Yumehanna]]'')\n| rowspan=2 | \u4e2d\u592e\u7dda\n| 1997<ref group=\"Note\">Owned by Osaka Port Transport System between [[Cosmosquare Station]] and [[\u014csakak\u014d Station]]</ref>\n| \u2013\n| {{convert|2.4|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 1<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[\u014csakak\u014d Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| 1961<ref group=\"Note\">Between [[\u014csakak\u014d Station]] and [[Nagata Station (Osaka)|Nagata Station]]</ref>\n| 1985\n| {{convert|15.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 13\n|-\n| ''Via trackage rights''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Keihanna Line]] (''[[Yumehanna]]'')''\n| \u8fd1\u9244\u3051\u3044\u306f\u3093\u306a\u7dda\n| ''1986''\n| ''2006''\n| ''{{convert|18.8|km|mi|abbr=on}}''\n| ''8''<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Nagata Station (Osaka)|Nagata Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background:#e44d93; color:white;\" | Pink\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[File:Osaka Metro Sennichimae line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 5\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Sennichimae Line]]\n| \u5343\u65e5\u524d\u7dda\n| 1969\n| 1981\n| {{convert|12.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 14\n|-\n| rowspan=3 style=\"background:#814721; color:white;\" | Brown\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Number prefix Hankyu Ky\u014dto line.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| rowspan=2 | ''Via trackage rights''\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Hankyu Senri Line]]''\n| \u962a\u6025\u5343\u91cc\u7dda \n| ''1969''\n| \u2013\n| ''{{convert|13.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}''\n| ''11''<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Tenjimbashisuji Rokuchome Station|Tenjimbashisuji Rokuch\u014dme Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Hankyu Kyoto Main Line]]''\n| \u962a\u6025\u4eac\u90fd\u672c\u7dda\n| ''1969''<ref group=\"Note\">Between [[Awaji Station]] and [[Kawaramachi Station (Kyoto)|Kawaramachi Station]]</ref>\n| \u2013\n| ''{{convert|41.1|km|mi|abbr=on}}''\n| ''22''<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Awaji Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[File:Osaka Metro Sakaisuji line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 6\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Sakaisuji Line]]\n| \u583a\u7b4b\u7dda\n| 1969\n| 1993\n| {{convert|8.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 10\n|-\n| style=\"background:#a9cc51\" | Lime\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 7\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]]\n| \u9577\u5800\u9db4\u898b\u7dd1\u5730\u7dda\n| 1990\n| 1997\n| {{convert|15.0|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 17\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ee7b1a\" | Orange\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Imazatosuji line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 8\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Imazatosuji Line]]\n| \u4eca\u91cc\u7b4b\u7dda \n| 2006\n| \u2013\n| {{convert|11.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 11\n|-\n| colspan=7 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''TOTAL (Subway only \u2013 not incl. ''trackage rights'' portions):'''\n| '''{{convert|129.9|km|mi|abbr=on}}'''\n| '''123'''\n|-\n! colspan=9 | [[People mover|Automated people mover]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2 style=\"background:#00a0de\" | Light <br> blue\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:center;\" |[[File:Osaka Metro Nanko Port Town line symbol.svg|22px]]\n| rowspan=2 | New Tram\n| rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:left;\" | [[Nank\u014d Port Town Line]]\n| rowspan=2 | \u5357\u6e2f\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8\u30bf\u30a6\u30f3\u7dda\n| 1997<ref group=\"Note\">Owned by Osaka Port Transport System between [[Cosmosquare Station]] and [[Trade Center-mae Station]]</ref>\n| \u2013\n| {{convert|0.7|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 1<ref group=\"Note\">Including [[Trade Center-mae Station]]</ref>\n|-\n| 1981<ref group=\"Note\">Between [[Trade Center-mae Station]] and [[Suminoekoen Station]]</ref>\n| 2005\n| {{convert|7.2|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| 9\n|-\n| colspan=7 style=\"text-align:center;\" | '''TOTAL (Subway, incl. People Mover):'''\n| '''{{convert|137.8|km|mi|abbr=on}}'''<ref name=\"overview\" />\n| '''133'''<ref name=\"overview\" />\n|}\n\n;Table notes\n{{Reflist|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n===Planned line and extensions===\n\nIn addition, there are five line extensions and one new line that are planned. However, on August 28, 2014, the [[Osaka Municipal Transportation Bureau]] met about creating the extensions of the later five of the six lines listed below, and have stated considering the current cost of the new extensions (and the possibly of privatization at the time), the government has also considered using [[light rail transit]] or [[bus rapid transit]] instead.<ref name=\"\u5730\u4e0b\u9244\uff14\u7dda\u5ef6\u4f38\">{{cite news | url=http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/local/osaka/news/20140829-OYTNT50036.html | script-title=ja:\u5730\u4e0b\u9244\uff14\u7dda\u5ef6\u4f38\u300c\u63a1\u7b97\u53b3\u3057\u3044\u300d\u3000\u6709\u8b58\u8005\u5be9\u8b70\u4f1a | work=[[Yomiuri Online]] | language=Japanese | date=August 29, 2014 | accessdate=September 1, 2014}}</ref> Osaka Metro is now experimenting with bus rapid transit on the route of the Imazatosuji Line extension, with \u201cImazato Liner\u201d service between Imazato and Yuzato-Rokuch\u014dme slated to begin in April 2019.\n\nWith Osaka being the host of [[Expo 2025]], there are also plans to extend the Chuo Line northwest onto Yume-shima (the event's planned site), with a terminus on Sakura-jima north of [[Universal Studios Japan]]. Provisions were put in place for such an extension when the existing road tunnel between Cosmosquare and Yume-shima was built, but the current state of the artificial island (with only industrial facilities and a lone convenience store for workers) meant it would have been unlikely to proceed had Osaka lost its bid.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Line <br />color\n! Mark\n! Line <br />number\n! Name\n! Start\n! Terminus\n! Length\n|-\n| style=\"background:#0078BE; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Yotsubashi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 3\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Yotsubashi Line]]\n| [[Nishi-Umeda Station|Nishi-Umeda]]\n| [[J\u016bs\u014d Station|J\u016bs\u014d]], later towards [[Shin-\u014csaka Station|Shin-\u014csaka]]\n| 2.9&nbsp;km (to J\u016bs\u014d)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#019A66; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Chuo line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 4\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]]\n| {{STN|Cosmosquare}}\n| Yumeshima\n| ''(TBD)''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#E44D93; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Sennichimae line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 5\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Sennichimae Line]]\n| [[Minami-Tatsumi Station|Minami-Tatsumi]]\n| towards [[Mito Station (Osaka)|Mito]]\n| ''(TBD)''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#A9CC51; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 7\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]]\n| [[Taish\u014d Station (Osaka)|Taish\u014d]]\n| Tsurumachi Yonch\u014dme (vicinity)\n| 5.5&nbsp;km\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EE7B1A; color:white;\" | &nbsp;\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[File:Osaka Metro Imazatosuji line symbol.svg|align=\"center\"|22px]]\n| Line 8\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Imazatosuji Line]]\n| [[Imazato Station (Osaka Municipal Subway)|Imazato]]\n| Yuzato Rokuch\u014dme\n| 6.7&nbsp;km\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFFFE0\"\n| ''(TBD)''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | -\n| [[Osaka Municipal Subway Line 9|Line 9]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Shikitsu\u2013Nagayoshi Line ''(provisional)''\n| [[Suminoek\u014den Station|Suminoek\u014den]]\n| [[Kire-Uriwari Station|Kire-Uriwari]]\n| 6.9&nbsp;km\n|}\n\n== Technology and rolling stock ==\nOsaka Municipal Subway [[rolling stock]] use two types of [[traction motor|propulsion systems]]. The vast majority of lines use trains with conventional [[electric motor]]s, but the two newest lines, the [[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]] and [[Imazatosuji Line]], use [[linear motor]]-powered trains, which allow them to use smaller trains and tunnels, reducing construction costs. These two lines have half-height [[automatic platform gates]] installed at all station platforms, as does the Sennichimae Line.<ref name=\"Sennichimae Line doors\">{{cite web | url=http://www.apt-newschannel.com/id/berita-berita/taiwan/detail/osaka-subways-sennichimae-line-to-have-platform-s/ | title=Osaka subway's Sennichimae Line to have platform screen doors installed in every station Chinese translation to follow | work=Asian Public Transport | date=February 13, 2014 | accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlso, unlike other rapid transit networks in Japan, most Osaka subway lines use a [[third rail]] electrification system for trains. Only three lines use [[overhead catenary]]: the Sakaisuji Line, to accommodate through services on Hankyu trackage; and the linear-motor Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi and Imazatosuji Lines. Also unusually, all lines use [[standard gauge]]; there are no [[narrow gauge]] sections of track due to the network being almost entirely self-enclosed.\n\n===Electric motored===\n* 10 series: [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]]\n* 20 series: [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]]\n* 21 series (\"[[Osaka Municipal Subway New 20 series|New 20 series]]\"): [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]]\n* 22 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Tanimachi Line]]\n* 23 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Yotsubashi Line]]\n* 24 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Ch\u016b\u014d Line (Osaka)|Ch\u016b\u014d Line]] (A variant of the 24 series is used on the Ch\u016b\u014d Line in Osaka Port Transport System livery.)\n* 25 series (\"New 20 series\"): [[Sennichimae Line]]\n* 66 series: [[Sakaisuji Line]]\n* [[Osaka Municipal Subway 30000 series|30000 series]]: [[Tanimachi Line]] and [[Mid\u014dsuji Line]]\n\n===Linear motored===\n* [[Osaka Municipal Subway 70 series|70 series]]: [[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]]\n* 80 series: [[Imazatosuji Line]]\n\n==Fares==\n[[File:Shinsaibashi Station 4.JPG|thumb|Ticket machines and fare maps at Shinsaibashi Station]]\nOsaka Metro charges five types of fares for single rides, based on the distance traveled in each journey.<ref name=\"tickets\">{{cite web |url=http://www.osakametro.co.jp/foreign/english/Fares.html |title=Tickets |publisher=Osaka Metro |date= |accessdate=April 14, 2018}}</ref> Some discount fares exist.\n\n{|class=wikitable\n|-\n! width=80px | Distance travelled\n! style=\"width:150px;\" | Rates (yen)<ref name=\"tickets\" />\n|-\n!width=80px|1\u20133&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 180 yen\n*children: 90 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|4\u20137&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 230 yen\n*children: 120 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|8\u201313&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 280 yen\n*children: 140 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|14\u201319&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 320 yen\n*children: 160 yen\n|-\n!width=80px|20\u201325&nbsp;km\n| style=\"width:150px;\"|\n*adults: 370 yen\n*children: 190 yen\n|}\n\n==Incidents==\nOn April 8, 1970, a gas explosion occurred during the construction of the [[Tanimachi Line]] at [[Tenjimbashisuji Rokuch\u014dme Station]], killing 79 people and injuring 420.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ja:\u5e02\u4f1a\u306e\u3042\u3086\u307f|url=http://www.city.osaka.lg.jp/shikai/page/0000001377.html|website=Osaka City Council Website|ref=\u5e02\u4f1a\u306e\u3042\u3086\u307f|language=Japanese|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pulvers|first=Roger|title=Beware the parallels between boom-time Japan and present-day China|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/opinion/2012/11/04/commentary/beware-the-parallels-between-boom-time-japan-and-present-day-china/#.U94OYRbOP-k|work=[[The Japan Times]]|ref=Parallels|date=November 4, 2012|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref> The gas leaked out from a detached joint and filled the tunnel and exploded, creating a fire pillar of over 10 meters and destroying 495 houses and buildings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gas Explosion at a Subway Construction Site|url=http://www.sozogaku.com/fkd/en/cfen/CB1012037.html|publisher=Failure Knowledge Center|ref=Case Details|accessdate=August 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Transport in Keihanshin]]\n* [[List of Osaka Metro stations]]\n* [[List of metro systems]]\n\n==References==\n{{notelist}}\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|\u014csaka Metro}}\n* [http://www.osakametro.co.jp/foreign/english/index.html Osaka Metro official site (English)]\n* [http://www.osakametro.co.jp/library/english/img/map.pdf Osaka Metro route map (PDF)]\n\n{{Metro systems in Japan}}\n{{Osaka transit}}\n\n[[Category:Osaka Municipal Subway|*]]\n[[Category:Underground rapid transit in Japan]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n[[Category:1500 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "name_user": "Killarnee", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File:Osaka Metro Logo.svg\u2192File:Osaka Metro former logo.svgFile renamed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osaka_Metro"}
{"title_page": "Greg Sheridan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name = Greg Sheridan\n| image = Mr.Greg Sheridan \u0e1a\u0e23\u0e23\u0e13\u0e32\u0e18\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e02\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e27\u0e38\u0e42\u0e2a\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e4c T - Flickr - Abhisit Vejjajiva.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Gregory Paul Sheridan\n| birth_date = 22 November 1956\n| birth_place = Inner-West Sydney\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1956|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| death_place = \n| occupation = Journalist\n| language = \n| children = \n| spouse = Jessie\n| nationality = Australian\n| website = [http://www.theaustralian.com.au/author/Greg+Sheridan Greg Sheridan - Author at The Australian]\n}}\n'''Gregory Paul '''\"'''Glassjaw Greg'''\"''' Sheridan''' {{postnom|country=AUS|AO}} (born 1956) is an [[Australia]]n [[foreign affairs]] [[journalist]] and [[Pundit|commentator]]. He has been the foreign editor of ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper since 1992. Not to be confused with Sheridan \u201cGreg\u201d Halls of Norfolk, UK.\n\n==Early life==\nSheridan grew up in [[Sydney]], attending Macquarie University and the University of Sydney but did not graduate.<ref>Sheridan, G.  (2015). ''When We Were Young & Foolish.'' Sydney: Allen & Unwin; {{ISBN|9781760113391}}, page 199.</ref> At university,  he was a close personal friend to [[Tony Abbott]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/tony-abbott-considered-appointing-the-australians-greg-sheridan-to-plum-posting-20150130-132101.html |title=Tony Abbott considered appointing The Australian's Greg Sheridan to plum posting |first=James |last=Massola |date=30 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202004121/http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/tony-abbott-considered-appointing-the-australians-greg-sheridan-to-plum-posting-20150130-132101.html |archivedate=2 February 2015 |url-status=live |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |publisher=Fairfax Media |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://newsweekly.com.au/article.php?id=57036|title=INTERVIEW- A politic apprenticeship: Greg Sheridan|first=Ticky|last=Fullerton|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306005201/http://newsweekly.com.au/article.php?id=57036|archivedate=6 March 2016}}</ref> the two attended the [[Australian Union of Students]] annual conference in Melbourne together, in 1977.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/tony-abbott-greg-sheridan-and-the-1977-aus-conference-a-political-baptism-of-fire/news-story/e2d004a14d411d5637e640b60ac363d6|newspaper=The Australian|publisher=News Corp Australia|title=Tony Abbott, Greg Sheridan and the 1977 AUS conference: a political baptism of fire|first=Greg|last=Sheridan|date=25 July 2015|quote=Edited extract from When We Were Young and Foolish}}</ref>  Sheridan also wrote some influential articles on the [[Macquarie science reform movement|sciences academic conflict]] at [[Macquarie University]].<ref>G. Sheridan, Australian physicist wins Guthrie Medal, ''The Bulletin'' '''101'''(5239), 49-50 (1980).</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=March 2016}}\nSheridan first worked at ''[[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]]'' magazine in 1979. His reporting on the Vietnamese boat people, subsequent to the end of the [[Vietnam War]], sparked a lifelong interest in Asian politics.\n\nSheridan joined ''The Australian'' in 1984.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/greg-sheridans-memoir-recalls-abbott-carr-early-days/news-story/092cdc38ecace8f7af756a33daedc0db|first=Peter|last=Craven|author-link=Peter Craven (literary critic)|newspaper=The Australian|date=1 August 2015|title=Greg Sheridan\u2019s memoir recalls Abbott, Carr early days|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> He worked in [[Beijing]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], and [[Canberra]] before starting his tenure as foreign editor in 1992. Writing on and from the [[Asia]]n region since the 1980s, he specialises on [[Politics of Asia|Asian politics]], and has written four books on the topic, plus a book on [[Australia\u2013United States relations|Australia\u2013U.S. relationships]]. He is a Distinguished Fellow of the Australia India Institute at the [[University of Melbourne]].\n\n==Commentary==\nSheridan has been a staunch supporter of closer ties between Australia and its [[Southeast Asia]]n neighbours, particularly [[Singapore]] and [[Indonesia]]. In his book ''Hidden Agendas'', journalist [[John Pilger]] accuses him of being a \"reliable ally\" of the [[Suharto]] dictatorship while serving as the foreign editor of ''The Australian''.<ref name=Pilger>{{cite book|last1=Pilger|first1=John|title=Hidden Agendas|date=1998|publisher=Vintage|isbn=9780099741510|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8v1TmtI6m5YC&q=greg+sheridan#v=snippet&q=greg%20sheridan&f=false|accessdate=2015-01-30}}</ref> In particular, Pilger derided Sheridan's defense of Indonesia following the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]]'s critique of Suharto's human rights records, as well as the Australian Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee following its confirmation of the [[Santa Cruz Massacre]]. Sheridan stated that \"even genuine victims frequently concoct stories\".<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/Books/In-praise-of-Soeharto-the-despot/2005/02/17/1108500195349.html In praise of Soeharto the despot], ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'', February 13, 2005</ref>\n\nHe was a vocal critic of [[Prime Minister]] [[John Howard|John Howard's]] intervention in [[East Timor]] in 1999, and during 2006 called for the removal of [[Mari Alkatiri]] as [[Prime Minister]] of that country.<ref>[https://www.crikey.com.au/2006/06/05/east-timor-is-no-failed-state/ East Timor is no failed state], [[Crikey]], June 5, 2006</ref>\n\nSheridan has been a supporter of the Australian government's [[Australian Anti-Terrorism Act 2005|anti-terror legislation]] and argued the deportation from Australia of [[United States|American]] environmental activist [[Scott Parkin]] was well founded.<ref>Sheridan, G., and Kerin, J. \"Deported activist was to teach tactics of violence\", ''[[The Australian]]'', 22 September 2005.</ref> He has also argued in support of the notion that [[George W. Bush]] will be judged \"one of the great presidents of the [[United States]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheridan|first1=Greg|title=A great president for these terrible times|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/a-great-president-for-these-terrible-times/story-e6frg6v6-1111112208118?nk=1ea832627b5d8ece09fcc96d17b7bbdd|accessdate=30 January 2015|work=The Australian|date=14 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn reference to the [[2011 Egyptian protests]], Sheridan wrote that \"What is happening in Egypt and across Arab North Africa more generally represents a distinct new phase in the existential crisis of Arab civilisation.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheridan|first1=Greg|title=Arab awakening or dawn of dark age|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/opinion/arab-awakening-or-dawn-of-dark-age/story-e6frg6zo-1225998985002|accessdate=30 January 2015|work=The Australian|date=3 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlthough originally from [[Sydney]], Sheridan moved to [[Melbourne]] in 2006. He is married to Jasbir Kaur \"Jessie\" Sheridan; the couple have three sons.<ref>Sheridan, Greg (1999). Asian Values, Western Dreams: Understanding the New Asia. Sydney: Allen & Unwin.<!-- ISSN/ISBN, page(s) needed --></ref>\nSheridan was given an Officer of the Order of Australia Honour in 2016, with the citation, \"For distinguished service to print media as a journalist and political commentator on foreign affairs and national security, and to Australia's bilateral relationships\".<ref>{{cite web |title=SHERIDAN, Gregory Paul |url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/1153704 |website=PMC |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* (editor and co-author) ''Living with Dragons: Australia Confronts Its Asian Destiny'' (Allen & Unwin, 1995; {{ISBN|1-86373-880-0}})\n*''Tigers: Leaders of the New Asia-Pacific'' (Allen & Unwin, 1997; {{ISBN|1-86448-153-6}})\n*''Asian Values, Western Dreams: Understanding the New Asia'' (Allen & Unwin, 1999; {{ISBN|1-86448-496-9}})\n*''Cities of the Hot Zone: A Southeast Asian Adventure'' (Allen & Unwin, 2003; {{ISBN|1-74114-224-5}})\n*''The Partnership: The Inside Story of the US-Australian Alliance Under Howard and Bush'' ([[University of New South Wales Press|UNSW Press]], 2006; {{ISBN|0-86840-922-7}})\n* ''When We Were Young & Foolish: A Memoir of My Misguided Youth with Tony Abbott, Bob Carr, Malcolm Turnbull, Kevin Rudd & Other Reprobates'' (Allen & Unwin, 2015; {{ISBN|9-78176-0113-391}})\n* ''God Is Good for You: A Defence of Christianity in Troubled Times'' (Allen & Unwin, 2018; {{ISBN|9-78176-0632-601}})\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051218074850/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5744,5974632%255E25378,00.html  About Greg Sheridan] on ''[[The Australian]]'' website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070603140622/http://blogs.theaustralian.news.com.au/gregsheridan/ Archive of Sheridan's articles] from 29 August 2006 onwards, with reader comments\n*[https://2001-2009.state.gov/secretary/rm/2006/63347.htm Sheridan interviews] [[United States Secretary of State]] [[Condoleezza Rice]], 15 March 2006\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Greg}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:The Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Macquarie University alumni]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=August 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name = Greg Sheridan\n| image = Mr.Greg Sheridan \u0e1a\u0e23\u0e23\u0e13\u0e32\u0e18\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e02\u0e48\u0e32\u0e27\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e27\u0e38\u0e42\u0e2a\u0e02\u0e2d\u0e07\u0e2b\u0e19\u0e31\u0e07\u0e2a\u0e37\u0e2d\u0e1e\u0e34\u0e21\u0e1e\u0e4c T - Flickr - Abhisit Vejjajiva.jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_name = Gregory Paul Sheridan\n| birth_date = 22 November 1956\n| birth_place = Inner-West Sydney\n| death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1956|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n| death_place = \n| occupation = Journalist\n| language = \n| children = \n| spouse = Jessie\n| nationality = Australian\n| website = [http://www.theaustralian.com.au/author/Greg+Sheridan Greg Sheridan - Author at The Australian]\n}}\n'''Gregory Paul '''\"'''Greg'''\"''' Sheridan''' {{postnom|country=AUS|AO}} (born 1956) is an [[Australia]]n [[foreign affairs]] [[journalist]] and [[Pundit|commentator]]. He has been the foreign editor of ''[[The Australian]]'' newspaper since 1992. Not to be confused with Sheridan \u201cGreg\u201d Halls of Norfolk, UK.\n\n==Early life==\nSheridan grew up in [[Sydney]], attending Macquarie University and the University of Sydney but did not graduate.<ref>Sheridan, G.  (2015). ''When We Were Young & Foolish.'' Sydney: Allen & Unwin; {{ISBN|9781760113391}}, page 199.</ref> At university,  he was a close personal friend to [[Tony Abbott]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/tony-abbott-considered-appointing-the-australians-greg-sheridan-to-plum-posting-20150130-132101.html |title=Tony Abbott considered appointing The Australian's Greg Sheridan to plum posting |first=James |last=Massola |date=30 January 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202004121/http://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/political-news/tony-abbott-considered-appointing-the-australians-greg-sheridan-to-plum-posting-20150130-132101.html |archivedate=2 February 2015 |url-status=live |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |publisher=Fairfax Media |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://newsweekly.com.au/article.php?id=57036|title=INTERVIEW- A politic apprenticeship: Greg Sheridan|first=Ticky|last=Fullerton|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306005201/http://newsweekly.com.au/article.php?id=57036|archivedate=6 March 2016}}</ref> the two attended the [[Australian Union of Students]] annual conference in Melbourne together, in 1977.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/life/weekend-australian-magazine/tony-abbott-greg-sheridan-and-the-1977-aus-conference-a-political-baptism-of-fire/news-story/e2d004a14d411d5637e640b60ac363d6|newspaper=The Australian|publisher=News Corp Australia|title=Tony Abbott, Greg Sheridan and the 1977 AUS conference: a political baptism of fire|first=Greg|last=Sheridan|date=25 July 2015|quote=Edited extract from When We Were Young and Foolish}}</ref>  Sheridan also wrote some influential articles on the [[Macquarie science reform movement|sciences academic conflict]] at [[Macquarie University]].<ref>G. Sheridan, Australian physicist wins Guthrie Medal, ''The Bulletin'' '''101'''(5239), 49-50 (1980).</ref>\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=March 2016}}\nSheridan first worked at ''[[The Bulletin (Australian periodical)|The Bulletin]]'' magazine in 1979. His reporting on the Vietnamese boat people, subsequent to the end of the [[Vietnam War]], sparked a lifelong interest in Asian politics.\n\nSheridan joined ''The Australian'' in 1984.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/arts/review/greg-sheridans-memoir-recalls-abbott-carr-early-days/news-story/092cdc38ecace8f7af756a33daedc0db|first=Peter|last=Craven|author-link=Peter Craven (literary critic)|newspaper=The Australian|date=1 August 2015|title=Greg Sheridan\u2019s memoir recalls Abbott, Carr early days|publisher=News Corp Australia|accessdate=12 April 2016}}</ref> He worked in [[Beijing]], [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], and [[Canberra]] before starting his tenure as foreign editor in 1992. Writing on and from the [[Asia]]n region since the 1980s, he specialises on [[Politics of Asia|Asian politics]], and has written four books on the topic, plus a book on [[Australia\u2013United States relations|Australia\u2013U.S. relationships]]. He is a Distinguished Fellow of the Australia India Institute at the [[University of Melbourne]].\n\n==Commentary==\nSheridan has been a staunch supporter of closer ties between Australia and its [[Southeast Asia]]n neighbours, particularly [[Singapore]] and [[Indonesia]]. In his book ''Hidden Agendas'', journalist [[John Pilger]] accuses him of being a \"reliable ally\" of the [[Suharto]] dictatorship while serving as the foreign editor of ''The Australian''.<ref name=Pilger>{{cite book|last1=Pilger|first1=John|title=Hidden Agendas|date=1998|publisher=Vintage|isbn=9780099741510|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8v1TmtI6m5YC&q=greg+sheridan#v=snippet&q=greg%20sheridan&f=false|accessdate=2015-01-30}}</ref> In particular, Pilger derided Sheridan's defense of Indonesia following the [[Bill Clinton|Clinton administration]]'s critique of Suharto's human rights records, as well as the Australian Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee following its confirmation of the [[Santa Cruz Massacre]]. Sheridan stated that \"even genuine victims frequently concoct stories\".<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/news/Books/In-praise-of-Soeharto-the-despot/2005/02/17/1108500195349.html In praise of Soeharto the despot], ''[[The Sun-Herald]]'', February 13, 2005</ref>\n\nHe was a vocal critic of [[Prime Minister]] [[John Howard|John Howard's]] intervention in [[East Timor]] in 1999, and during 2006 called for the removal of [[Mari Alkatiri]] as [[Prime Minister]] of that country.<ref>[https://www.crikey.com.au/2006/06/05/east-timor-is-no-failed-state/ East Timor is no failed state], [[Crikey]], June 5, 2006</ref>\n\nSheridan has been a supporter of the Australian government's [[Australian Anti-Terrorism Act 2005|anti-terror legislation]] and argued the deportation from Australia of [[United States|American]] environmental activist [[Scott Parkin]] was well founded.<ref>Sheridan, G., and Kerin, J. \"Deported activist was to teach tactics of violence\", ''[[The Australian]]'', 22 September 2005.</ref> He has also argued in support of the notion that [[George W. Bush]] will be judged \"one of the great presidents of the [[United States]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheridan|first1=Greg|title=A great president for these terrible times|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/archive/news/a-great-president-for-these-terrible-times/story-e6frg6v6-1111112208118?nk=1ea832627b5d8ece09fcc96d17b7bbdd|accessdate=30 January 2015|work=The Australian|date=14 September 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn reference to the [[2011 Egyptian protests]], Sheridan wrote that \"What is happening in Egypt and across Arab North Africa more generally represents a distinct new phase in the existential crisis of Arab civilisation.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheridan|first1=Greg|title=Arab awakening or dawn of dark age|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/opinion/arab-awakening-or-dawn-of-dark-age/story-e6frg6zo-1225998985002|accessdate=30 January 2015|work=The Australian|date=3 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAlthough originally from [[Sydney]], Sheridan moved to [[Melbourne]] in 2006. He is married to Jasbir Kaur \"Jessie\" Sheridan; the couple have three sons.<ref>Sheridan, Greg (1999). Asian Values, Western Dreams: Understanding the New Asia. Sydney: Allen & Unwin.<!-- ISSN/ISBN, page(s) needed --></ref>\nSheridan was given an Officer of the Order of Australia Honour in 2016, with the citation, \"For distinguished service to print media as a journalist and political commentator on foreign affairs and national security, and to Australia's bilateral relationships\".<ref>{{cite web |title=SHERIDAN, Gregory Paul |url=https://honours.pmc.gov.au/honours/awards/1153704 |website=PMC |accessdate=17 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* (editor and co-author) ''Living with Dragons: Australia Confronts Its Asian Destiny'' (Allen & Unwin, 1995; {{ISBN|1-86373-880-0}})\n*''Tigers: Leaders of the New Asia-Pacific'' (Allen & Unwin, 1997; {{ISBN|1-86448-153-6}})\n*''Asian Values, Western Dreams: Understanding the New Asia'' (Allen & Unwin, 1999; {{ISBN|1-86448-496-9}})\n*''Cities of the Hot Zone: A Southeast Asian Adventure'' (Allen & Unwin, 2003; {{ISBN|1-74114-224-5}})\n*''The Partnership: The Inside Story of the US-Australian Alliance Under Howard and Bush'' ([[University of New South Wales Press|UNSW Press]], 2006; {{ISBN|0-86840-922-7}})\n* ''When We Were Young & Foolish: A Memoir of My Misguided Youth with Tony Abbott, Bob Carr, Malcolm Turnbull, Kevin Rudd & Other Reprobates'' (Allen & Unwin, 2015; {{ISBN|9-78176-0113-391}})\n* ''God Is Good for You: A Defence of Christianity in Troubled Times'' (Allen & Unwin, 2018; {{ISBN|9-78176-0632-601}})\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051218074850/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/common/story_page/0,5744,5974632%255E25378,00.html  About Greg Sheridan] on ''[[The Australian]]'' website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070603140622/http://blogs.theaustralian.news.com.au/gregsheridan/ Archive of Sheridan's articles] from 29 August 2006 onwards, with reader comments\n*[https://2001-2009.state.gov/secretary/rm/2006/63347.htm Sheridan interviews] [[United States Secretary of State]] [[Condoleezza Rice]], 15 March 2006\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheridan, Greg}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:The Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:Macquarie University alumni]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n", "name_user": "121.45.222.23", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greg_Sheridan"}
{"title_page": "Peter Bangs Vej", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = Peter Bangs Vej\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Peter Bangs Vej Copenhagen.JPG\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = \n| former_names    = \n| length_m        = 2780\n| width           =\n| location        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| quarter                 = [[Frederiksberg]]\n| postal_code     = 1619, 1859\n| metro                   = [[Peter Bangs Vej station|Peter Bangs Vej]], [[Fasanvej Station|Fasanvej]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|43.68|N|12|30|25.92|E}}\n| direction_a             = Northeast\n| terminus_a              = [[Smallegade]]\n| direction_b             = Sputhwest\n| terminus_b              = [[Roskildevej]]\n| junction                = [[Dalgas Boulevard]], [[Ring 2 (Copenhagen)|Ring 2]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Peter Bangs Vej''' is a 2.2&nbsp;km long street in [[Frederiksberg]],  a city in the Copenhagen area on the island of [[Zealand (Denmark)|Zealand]], [[Denmark]]. The direct continuation of [[Smallegade]], it initially runs west, from [[Nordre Fasanvej]], but then turns south along the east side of [[Damhuss\u00f8en|Damhus Lake]] to meet [[Roskildevej]]. There is a large sports complex on the south end of the street with the football club [[F.C. Copenhagen]]'s training facilities as well as the multi-purpose venue [[K.B. Hallen]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Diakonissestiftelsen (1873).jpg|thumb|left|Peter Bangs Vej with [[Diakonissestiftelsen]]]]\nA field track referred to as Klammerivejen (literally Vrewl Road) followed the same route from at least 1755. It is probably older since documents from 1688 mentions \"Clammerijs Agre\". A popular but unverifiable explanation of the name is that the road was too narrow for two carriages to pass and that it was therefore liable to cause disputes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taxafinn.dk/hovedstadensgadenavne.htm|title=Hovedstadens gadenavnes betydning|language=Danish|publisher=taxafinn.dk|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> The track was the direct continuation of the [[Gammel Kongevej]] road which connected Copenhagen's Western City Gate to the village of Solbjerg, whose village pond can still be seen on the south side of Smallegade.\n\n[[File:Peter Bangs Vej (1913).jpg|thumb|200px|Peter Bangs Vej in 1913]]\nThe road received its current name on 8 October 1868. It was named after the politician Peter Georg Bang who had recently died. The first major building along the road was [[Diakonissestiftelsen]]'s hospital from 1876. The old West Line crossed the road just east of present-day Lindevangs All\u00e9. In 1914, the road was regulated and a tram line to [[Vanl\u00f8se]] was inaugurated on 8 December that same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kobenhavnshistorie.dk/bog/khsd/1900/1914.html|title=1914|language=Danish|publisher=Selskabet for K\u00f8benhavns Historie|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> Several large factories were built in the area between Peter Bangs Vej and [[Finsensvej]] in the 1900s and 1910s, such as [[Nilfisk-Advance|Fisker & Nielsen]]'s factory from 1913.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taxafinn.dk/frederiksbergvejnavne2.htm|title=Veje p\u00e5 Frederiksberg|language=Danish|publisher=Frederiksberg Kommune|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> The company both manufactured their [[Nilfisk]] [[vacuum cleaner]]s and their [[Nimbus (motorcycle)|Nimbus]] motorcycles at the site.\n\n[[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub]], Copenhagen's first ball-playing club, acquired a 6 hectares site on the south side of Peter Bangs Vej in 1924. The club inaugurated a large new sports complex at the site on 10 April 1928.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dbukoebenhavn.dk/oevrigt_indhold/DBUK_Historie/Spillestedernes%20historie/KB%20Peter%20Bangsvej.aspx|title=Peter Bangs Vej|language=Danish|publisher=Dansk Boldspil Union|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\n[[File:Danish Union of Librarians.jpg|thumb|150px|Danish Union of Librarians' building]] \n[[Image:Dk frb diakonisse.JPG|thumb|left|Diakonissestiftelsen seen from Peter Bangs Vej]]\n[[Diakonissestiftelsen]]'s old main building  (No. 1) is from 1876 and was designed by [[Hans J\u00f8rgen Holm]] in the style of a Medieval convent. The Deaconess Foundation has launched a 2020 plan for a comprehensive redevelopment of their site with residences as well as social and healthcare facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diakonissestiftelsen.dk/Default.aspx?ID=104&M=News&PID=473&NewsID=1042|title=To vindere i konkurrencen om Diakonissestiftelsen|language=Danish|publisher=Diakonissestiftelsen|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe building Sarepta designed by [[Carl Lendorf]] (No. 8) and Teba (No. 10), both from the 1880s and located on the other side of the street, were also built of Diakonissestiftelsen. They have now been converted into the daycare Marthag\u00e5rden with a distinctive modern extension by Landager Arkitekter in 2013\u201314.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkark.dk/building.aspx?buildingid=14066|title=Marthag\u00e5rden, Frederiksberglanguage=Danish|website=arkark.dk|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> To the rear of the two buildings stands the [[Postmodernism|Postmodern]], round headquarters of the Danish Union of Librarians. It was designed by [[Knud Munk]].\n\n[[Image:Den hvide by - Frederiksberg house.jpg|thumb|left|One of the [[White Houses, Frederiksberg|White Houses]] on a side street to Peter Bangs Vej]]\nThe [[White Houses, Frederiksberg|White Houses]], situated a little further out, is a [[building society]] development originally built for workers at Frederiksberg Gasworks in the 1890s. The architect was Gotfred Tvede. Lindevang Church (No. 69) is from 1825 to 1830 and was designed by [[Thomas Havning]] and Anton Frederiksen.\n\nFisker & Nielsen's former factory site was redeveloped between 2002 and 2008 and is now known as [[Nimbusparken]] (Peter Bangs Vej 30/ H. V. Nyholms Vej). It contains a mixture of residential and commercial buildings and reuses some of the old industrial buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkark.dk/building.aspx?buildingid=2116|title=Nimbusparken, Frederiksberg|language=Danish|website=arkark.dk|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/ny-bydel-med-duft-af-nimbus-31911|title=Ny bydel med duft af Nimbus|language=Danish|publisher=Ingeni\u00f8ren|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> The [[Danish Association of Masters and PhDs]] is based in the building directly on the street (No. 30).\n\n[[Image:K.B. Hallen 01.jpg|thumb|No. 147: [[K.B. Hallen]] ]]\n[[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub]]'s extensive sports complex at Peter Bangs Vej is the primary training grounds of [[F.C. Copenhagen]]. The site also included the listed multi-purpose venue [[K.B. Hallen]] venue from 1938 but it was destroyed in a fire in 2011. [[Christensen & Co]] has won a competition to build a new KB-Hallen to a new design inspired by the old building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://byensejendom.dk/article/-christensen--co-skal-designe-den-ny-kb-hal-til-150-millioner-15739|title=Christensen & Co skal designe den ny KB Hal til 150 millioner|language=Danish|website=Byens Ejendomme|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Parks and open spaces==\nSeveral green spaces are located along the street. [[Lindevangsparken]] is located just north of the park. It was created and 1932 and has an area of 33,000 square metres, making it the largest and oldest municipal park in Frederiksberg. The much larger and older [[Frederiksberg Park]] and [[S\u00f8ndermarken]] are state-owned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frb-forsyning.dk/Default.aspx?ID=324&m=News&PID=831&NewsID=438|title=Lindevangsparken: Skybrud, leg og l\u00e6ring er p\u00e5 vej|language=Danish|publisher=Frederiksberg Forsyning|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> The [[Damhuss\u00f8en|Damhus Lake]] and adjoining Damhus Meadow in [[Vanl\u00f8se]] is located just west of the street.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Peter Bangs Vej station]] is located on the [[Frederikssundbanen|Frederikssund radial]] of the [[S-train]] network and is served by the [[C (S-train)|C]] trains. [[KB Hallen station]] is located on the [[Ringbanen|Ring Line]] between [[Hellerup station|Hellerup]] and [[Ny Ellebjerg station|Ny Ellebjerg]] and is served by [[G (S-train)|F]].\n\nThe Inner Ring Route of Copenhagen's [[Super Bikeways in metropolitan Copenhagen|super bikeway network]] passes Diakonissestiftelsen]] on tis way from [[Emdrup]] to [[Valby]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.arkitekturbilleder.dk/bygning-B%C3%B8rnehuset-Marthag%C3%A5rden-924 Marthag\u00e5rden] at arkitekturbilleder, dk\n\n{{Frederiksberg}}\n\n{{coord|55.6788|N|12.5072|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Frederiksberg]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = Peter Bangs Vej\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Peter Bangs Vej Copenhagen.JPG\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = \n| former_names    = \n| length_m        = 2780\n| width           =\n| location        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| quarter                 = [[Frederiksberg]]\n| postal_code     = 1619, 1859\n| metro                   = [[Peter Bangs Vej station|Peter Bangs Vej]], [[Fasanvej Station|Fasanvej]]\n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|40|43.68|N|12|30|25.92|E}}\n| direction_a             = Northeast\n| terminus_a              = [[Smallegade]]\n| direction_b             = Sputhwest\n| terminus_b              = [[Roskildevej]]\n| junction                = [[Dalgas Boulevard]], [[Ring 2 (Copenhagen)|Ring 2]]\n}}\n\n\n'''Peter Bangs Vej''' is a 2.2&nbsp;km long street in [[Frederiksberg]],  a city in the Copenhagen area on the island of [[Zealand (Denmark)|Zealand]], [[Denmark]]. The direct continuation of [[Smallegade]], it initially runs west, from [[Nordre Fasanvej]], but then turns south along the east side of [[Damhuss\u00f8en|Damhus Lake]] to meet [[Roskildevej]]. There is a large sports complex on the south end of the street with the football club [[F.C. Copenhagen]]'s training facilities as well as the multi-purpose venue [[K.B. Hallen]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Diakonissestiftelsen (1873).jpg|thumb|left|Peter Bangs Vej with [[Diakonissestiftelsen]]]]\nA field track referred to as Klammerivejen (literally Vrewl Road) followed the same route from at least 1755. It is probably older since documents from 1688 mentions \"Clammerijs Agre\". A popular but unverifiable explanation of the name is that the road was too narrow for two carriages to pass and that it was therefore liable to cause disputes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taxafinn.dk/hovedstadensgadenavne.htm|title=Hovedstadens gadenavnes betydning|language=Danish|publisher=taxafinn.dk|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> The track was the direct continuation of the [[Gammel Kongevej]] road which connected Copenhagen's Western City Gate to the village of Solbjerg, whose village pond can still be seen on the south side of Smallegade.\n\n[[File:Peter Bangs Vej (1913).jpg|thumb|200px|Peter Bangs Vej in 1913]]\nThe road received its current name on 8 October 1868. It was named after the politician Peter Georg Bang who had recently died. The first major building along the road was [[Diakonissestiftelsen]]'s hospital from 1876. The old West Line crossed the road just east of present-day Lindevangs All\u00e9. In 1914, the road was regulated and a tram line to [[Vanl\u00f8se]] was inaugurated on 8 December that same year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kobenhavnshistorie.dk/bog/khsd/1900/1914.html|title=1914|language=Danish|publisher=Selskabet for K\u00f8benhavns Historie|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> Several large factories were built in the area between Peter Bangs Vej and [[Finsensvej]] in the 1900s and 1910s, such as [[Nilfisk-Advance|Fisker & Nielsen]]'s factory from 1913.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taxafinn.dk/frederiksbergvejnavne2.htm|title=Veje p\u00e5 Frederiksberg|language=Danish|publisher=Frederiksberg Kommune|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref> The company both manufactured their [[Nilfisk]] [[vacuum cleaner]]s and their [[Nimbus (motorcycle)|Nimbus]] motorcycles at the site.\n\n[[Kj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub]], Copenhagen's first ball-playing club, acquired a 6 hectares site on the south side of Peter Bangs Vej in 1924. The club inaugurated a large new sports complex at the site on 10 April 1928.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dbukoebenhavn.dk/oevrigt_indhold/DBUK_Historie/Spillestedernes%20historie/KB%20Peter%20Bangsvej.aspx|title=Peter Bangs Vej|language=Danish|publisher=Dansk Boldspil Union|accessdate=3 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\n[[File:Danish Union of Librarians.jpg|thumb|150px|Danish Union of Librarians' building]] \n[[Image:Dk frb diakonisse.JPG|thumb|left|Diakonissestiftelsen seen from Peter Bangs Vej]]\n[[Diakonissestiftelsen]]'s old main building  (No. 1) is from opf\u00f8rtes 1876 and was designed by [[Hans J\u00f8rgen Holm]] in the style of a Medieval convent. The Deaconess Foundation has launched a 2020 plan for a comprehensive redevelopment of their site with residences as well as social and healthcare facilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diakonissestiftelsen.dk/Default.aspx?ID=104&M=News&PID=473&NewsID=1042|title=To vindere i konkurrencen om Diakonissestiftelsen|language=Danish|publisher=Diakonissestiftelsen|accessdate=25 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe building Sarepta designed by [[Carl Lendorf]] (No. 8) and Teba (No. 10), both from the 1880s and located on the other side of the street, were also built of Diakonissestiftelsen. They have now been converted into the daycare Marthag\u00e5rden with a distinctive modern extension byLandager Arkitekter in 2013\u201314.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkark.dk/building.aspx?buildingid=14066|title=Marthag\u00e5rden, Frederiksberglanguage=Danish|website=arkark.dk|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> To the rear of the two buildings stands the [[Postmodernism|Postmodern]], round headquarters of the Danish Union of Librarians. It was designed by [[Knud Munk]].\n\n[[Image:Den hvide by - Frederiksberg house.jpg|thumb|left|One of the [[White Houses, Frederiksberg|White Houses]] on a side street to Peter Bangs Vej]]\nThe [[White Houses, Frederiksberg|White Houses]], situated a little further out, is a [[building society]] development originally built for workers at Frederiksberg Gasworks in the 1890s. The architect was Getfred Tvede. Lindevang Church (No. 69) is from 1825 to 1830 and was designed by [[Thomas Havning]] and Anton Frederiksen.\n\nFisker & Nielsen's former factory site was redeveloped between 2002 and 2008 and is now known as [[Nimnusparken]] (Peter Bangs Vej 30/ H. V. Nyholms Vej). It contains a mixture of residential and commercial buildings and reuses some of the old industrial buildings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arkark.dk/building.aspx?buildingid=2116|title=Nimbusparken, Frederiksberg|language=Danish|website=arkark.dk|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ing.dk/artikel/ny-bydel-med-duft-af-nimbus-31911|title=Ny bydel med duft af Nimbus|language=Danish|publisher=Ingeni\u00f8ren|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> The [[Danish Association of Masters and PhDs]] is based in the building directly on the street (No. 30).\n\n[[Image:K.B. Hallen 01.jpg|thumb|No. 147: [[K.B. Hallen]] ]]\n[[Jj\u00f8benhavns Boldklub]]'s extensive sports complex at Peter Bangs Vej is the primary training grounds of [[F.C. Copenhagen]]. The site also included the listed multi-purpose venue [[K.B. Hallen]] venue from 1938 but ir was destroyed in a fire in 2011. [[Christensen & Co]] has won a competition to build a new KB-Hallen to a new design inspired by the old building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://byensejendom.dk/article/-christensen--co-skal-designe-den-ny-kb-hal-til-150-millioner-15739|title=Christensen & Co skal designe den ny KB Hal til 150 millioner|language=Danish|website=Byens Ejendomme|accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Parks and open spaces==\nSeveral green spaces are located along the street. [[Lindevangsparken]] is located just north of the park. It was created and 1932 and has an area of 33,000 square metres, making it the largest and oldest municipal park in Frederiksberg. The much larger and older [[Frederiksberg Park]] and [[S\u00f8ndermarken]] are state-owned.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frb-forsyning.dk/Default.aspx?ID=324&m=News&PID=831&NewsID=438|title=Lindevangsparken: Skybrud, leg og l\u00e6ring er p\u00e5 vej|language=Danish|publisher=Frederiksberg Forsyning|accessdate=5 February 2016}}</ref> The [[Damhuss\u00f8en|Damhus Lake]] and adjoining Damhus Meadow in [[Vanl\u00f8se]] is located just west of the street.\n\n==Transport==\n[[Peter Bangs Vej station]] is located on the [[Frederikssundbanen|Frederikssund radial]] of the [[S-train]] network and is served by the [[C (S-train)|C]] trains. [[KB Hallen station]] is located on the [[Ringbanen|Ring Line]] between [[Hellerup station|Hellerup]] and [[Ny Ellebjerg station|Ny Ellebjerg]] and is served by [[G (S-train)|F]].\n\nThe Inner Ring Route of Copenhagen's [[Super Bikeways in metropolitan Copenhagen|super bikeway network]] passes Diakonissestiftelsen]] on tis way from [[Emdrup]] to [[Valby]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons}}\n* [http://www.arkitekturbilleder.dk/bygning-B%C3%B8rnehuset-Marthag%C3%A5rden-924 Marthag\u00e5rden] at arkitekturbilleder, dk\n\n{{Frederiksberg}}\n\n{{coord|55.6788|N|12.5072|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in Frederiksberg]]\n", "name_user": "Tagg", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotable buildings and residents:typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Bangs_Vej"}
{"title_page": "Romblon", "text_new": "{{About||the capital town|Romblon, Romblon|other uses}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Romblon\n| official_name           = Province of Romblon\n| settlement_type         = {{PH wikidata|settlement_type}}\n| image_skyline           = {{Photomontage\n| photo1a  = Romblon_island_040col.jpg\n| photo2a  = Fort San Andres 6.JPG \n| photo2b  = St. Joseph Cathedral 15.JPG\n| photo3a  = MainitFalls81027cga.jpg\n| photo3b  = Binucot Beach.jpg\n| size     = 250\n| position = center\n| spacing  = 2\n| color    = transparent\n| border   = 0 \n}}\n| image_caption           = (From top, left to right) {{hlist | Romblon Bay with the capital town of Romblon in the foreground | Fort San Andres | the Cathedral of St. Joseph the Worker Parish | Mainit Falls in Odiongan | Binucot Beach in Odiongan}}\n| image_flag              = {{PH wikidata|image_flag}}\n| flag_size               = 120x80px\n| image_seal              = Ph_seal_romblon.png\n| seal_size               = 100x80px\n| image_shield            = \n| nickname                = ''Marble Capital of the Philippines''\n| image_map               = {{PH wikidata|image_map}}\n| map_caption             = Location in the Philippines\n| image_map1             = {{Infobox mapframe|id={{#invoke:Wikibase|id}}}}\n| coordinates             = {{PH wikidata|coordinates}}\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = {{PH wikidata|country}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Regions of the Philippines|Region]]\n| subdivision_name1       = {{PH wikidata|region}}\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = March 16, 1901\n| seat_type               = Capital\n| seat                    = {{PH wikidata|seat}}\n| government_type         = {{PH wikidata|government_type}}\n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = [[Governor of Romblon|Governor]]\n| leader_name             = Jose R. Riano ([[PDP-Laban]])\n| leader_title1           = [[Vice Governor]]\n| leader_name1            = Felix F. Ylagan ([[Lakas-CMD|LAKAS]])\n| leader_title2           = Representative\n| leader_name2            = Eleandro Jesus F. Madrona ([[Nacionalista Party|Nacionalista]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://halalanresults.abs-cbn.com/|title=Halalan 2019 Philippine Election Results|website=ABS-CBN News}}</ref><ref name=\"COMELEC2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.comelec.gov.ph/?r=Archives/RegularElections/2013NLE/Results/congress2013 |title=Congressional Election Results: Romblon |work=May 13, 2013 National and Local Elections |date=12 May 2014 |location=Manila: Commission on Elections |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref><br> {{small|[[Legislative district of Romblon|Lone District]]}}\n| area_footnotes          = <ref name=nscblist>{{cite web |title=List of Provinces |url=http://www.nscb.gov.ph/activestats/psgc/listprov.asp |work=PSGC Interactive |publisher=National Statistical Coordination Board |accessdate=31 January 2013 |location=Makati City, Philippines}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = {{PH wikidata|area}}\n| area_rank               = 68th out of 81\n| elevation_max_m         = 2,058\n| elevation_max_point     = [[Mount Guiting-Guiting]]\n| population_footnotes    = {{PH census|current|04B}}\n| population_total        = {{PH wikidata|population_total}}\n| population_as_of        = {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}\n| population_rank         = 66th out of 81\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_rank = 46th out of 81\n| demographics_type1      = Divisions\n| demographics1_title1    = [[Cities of the Philippines#Independent cities|Independent&nbsp;cities]]\n| demographics1_info1     = 0\n| demographics1_title2    = [[Cities of the Philippines|Component cities]]\n| demographics1_info2     = 0\n| demographics1_title3    = [[Municipalities of the Philippines|Municipalities]]\n| demographics1_info3     = {{Collapsible list\n| titlestyle              = font-weight:normal;text-align:left;background-color:WhiteSmoke;\n| title                   = 17\n | {{PH wikidata|municipalities}}\n}}\n| demographics1_title4    = [[Barangay]]s\n| demographics1_info4     = 219\n| demographics1_title5    = [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Districts]]\n| demographics1_info5     = [[Legislative district of Romblon|Lone district of Romblon]]\n| timezone                = [[Philippine Standard Time|PHT]]\n| utc_offset              = +08:00\n| postal_code_type        = [[List of ZIP codes in the Philippines|ZIP Code]]\n| postal_code             = {{PH wikidata|postal_code}}\n| area_code_type          = {{areacodestyle}}\n| area_code               = {{PH wikidata|area_code}}\n| iso_code                = {{PH wikidata|iso_code}}\n| blank_name_sec1         = Spoken languages\n| blank_info_sec1         = {{hlist | [[Romblomanon language|Romblomanon]] | [[Onhan language|Onhan]] | [[Asi language|Asi]] | [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]] | [[Filipino language|Filipino]] | [[English language|English]] }}\n| website                 = {{Official URL}}\n}}\n'''Romblon''' ({{IPAc-en|r|\u0252|m|\u02c8|b|l|o\u028a|n}} {{respell|rom|BLOHN|'}}) is an archipelagic [[Provinces of the Philippines|province]] of the [[Philippines]] located in the [[Mimaropa]] [[Regions of the Philippines|region]]. Its main islands include [[Tablas Island|Tablas]], the largest, which covers nine municipalities, [[Sibuyan Island|Sibuyan]] with its three towns, as well as the smaller island municipalities of [[Corcuera, Romblon|Corcuera]], [[Banton, Romblon|Banton]], [[Concepcion, Romblon|Concepcion]], [[San Jose, Romblon|San Jose]], and [[Romblon, Romblon|Romblon]], the provincial capital. The province lies south of [[Marinduque]] and [[Quezon]], east of [[Oriental Mindoro]], north of [[Aklan Province|Aklan]] and [[Capiz Province|Capiz]], and west of [[Masbate]]. According to the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}}, it has a total population of {{PH wikidata|population_total}}.{{PH census|current|04B}}\n\nRomblon has been inhabited by aboriginal Filipinos prior to the arrival of the Spanish in 1569. Archaeological artifacts recovered by the [[National Museum of the Philippines|National Museum]] in 1936 indicate that the aborigines of Romblon already have a rich and advanced culture. Under Spanish colonial rule, Romblon was initially administered under the newly established province of [[Iloilo|Arevalo]], until 1716, when it was transferred to the jurisdiction of the newly created province of [[Capiz]]. With arrival of the Americans in 1901, Romblon was declared a province and placed under civilian rule. It lost its provincial status for a short while between 1907 and 1945, but regained it in 1946, just after [[World War II]].\n\nThe inhabitants of Romblon are divided into three ethnolinguistic groups: [[Romblomanon language|Romblomanon]], [[Onhan language|Onhan]] and [[Asi language|Asi]]. These groups occupy specific islands in the province and have their own language and customs. Romblomanon is mainly spoken in the town of Romblon, in all of three towns of Sibuyan Island, and the town of [[San Agustin, Romblon|San Agustin]] in Tablas Island. Onhan is mainly spoken in the municipalities in the southern part of Tablas Island ([[Alcantara, Romblon|Alcantara]], [[Looc, Romblon|Looc]], [[Ferrol, Romblon|Ferrol]], [[Santa Fe, Romblon|Santa Fe]], [[San Andres, Romblon|San Andres]], and [[Santa Maria, Romblon|Santa Maria]]) as well as in the island municipality of San Jose. The northwestern part of Tablas Island (in [[Odiongan, Romblon|Odiongan]] and [[Calatrava, Romblon|Calatrava]], as well as the islands municipalities of Corcuera, Banton, and Concepcion, speak the Asi language.\n\nCurrently, the province relies on [[agriculture]], particularly [[rice]] and [[copra]] farming as well as [[fishing]], for its livelihood. It also has a lucrative [[marble]] industry due to an abundance of Italian-quality marble, hence, its moniker as the \"Marble Capital of the Philippines.\" In recent years, the province has also become an [[ecotourism]] destination, with several white sand beaches, diving spots, mountains and rainforests that tourists visit annually.\n\n==Etymology==\nAccording to legend, the name \"Romblon\" was derived from the Romblomanon word ''Nagalumyom'', which pertains to a chicken in the act of [[broodiness|sitting on its eggs]] on a nest.<ref name=\"Prado\">Local historian Francis Ray Prado details the legend, saying that when the Spanish, led by [[conquistador]] [[Martin de Goiti]], arrived in Romblon in 1569, they wandered along the island's beaches searching for food and water. One of the men encountered a hut with a hen's nest on top of a post near its window. The man asked the house's occupant, a young woman, if he could have the hen for free, but the woman, unable to understand Spanish, answered, \"''Nagalumyom!''\" which in the local language means \"the hen was brooding eggs.\" {{cite book |title=The History of Carmen Including Historical and Cultural Background of North-eastern Barangays of the Municipality of San Agustin, Romblon |author=Prado, Francis Ray |year=2005 |page=15 |publisher=Private publication }}</ref> This eventually evolved to ''Lomlom'', and later on to ''Donblon'', the name reported by Spanish [[chronicler]] Miguel de Loarca in his book ''Relacion de las Islas Filipinas'' in  1582, before finally evolving to Romblon.<ref name=\"Loarca\">{{cite book |url=http://www.gutenberg.org/files/16501/16501-h/16501-h.htm |title=Relacion de las Islas Filipinas by Miguel de Loarca |work=The Philippine Islands, 1493\u20131803 Volume V., 1582\u20131583 |author1=Blair, Emma  |author2=Robertson, James Alexander  |lastauthoramp=yes |date=9 August 2005 |publisher=Project Gutenberg |accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, local historians Roland Madeja and Evelyn Reyes relate the origin of the name \"Romblon\" to the shape of Romblon Island. Madeja claims that the name was derived from the [[Spanish language|Spanish]] word ''ronblon'', another term for ''tornillo'', meaning \"[[screw]].\" According to him, the Spanish claimed to have observed the screw-like shape of Romblon Island.<ref name=\"Madeja\">{{cite book |title=Romblon Province, 1570\u20131946: Its History and Development |last=Madeja |first=Roland F. |page=38 |year=1993 |location=Manila: Manuel Luis Quezon University |ref=harv}}</ref> Meanwhile, Reyes claims Romblon originated from \"[[Spanish dollar|doubloon]]\", which refers to the Spanish coin used by [[Moro people|Moro]] pirates in paying [[dowry|dowries]] for their brides-to-be. The Spanish might have named the island after the shape of the coin.<ref name=\"Reyes\">{{cite book |last=Reyes |first=Evelyn M. |year=1995 |title=Romblon During American Regime, 1898\u20131946 |location=Manila: De La Salle University |page=12|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ipot Cave.JPG|left|thumb|Ipot Cave in [[Banton, Romblon|Banton]], where the earliest known warp ''[[ikat]]'' textile in [[Southeast Asia]] was found in 1936]]\n\n===Early history===\nRomblon's aboriginal inhabitants were the [[Negrito]]s from [[Panay Island|Panay]] and [[Mangyan]]s from [[Mindoro]], who settled in the islands during the precolonial period.<ref name=\"RomblonProv\">{{cite web |url=http://www.romblonprov.gov.ph/pages.php?m=romblon_province |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131123082200/http://www.romblonprov.gov.ph/pages.php?m=romblon_province |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 November 2013 |title=History |work=Romblon Province |publisher=Romblon Provincial Government |accessdate=8 September 2015 }}</ref> Ancient wooden coffins discovered in the Guyangan Cave System of [[Banton, Romblon|Banton Island]] in 1936 signify a rich ancient civilization and culture in the province before the arrival of the Spaniards in 1569. These artifacts are currently on display at the National Museum in [[Manila]].<ref name=Banton>[http://www.yagting.com/bantonvol01/briefhistory.asp Brief History of Banton] The Official Website of Banton, Romblon. Retrieved on 2013-03-30</ref> Remnants of Negrito and Mangyan aborigines now live in the mountains of [[Tablas Island|Tablas]] and [[Sibuyan Island|Sibuyan]] after they were displaced by the influx of [[Hiligaynon people|Hiligaynon]], [[Aklanon people|Aklanon]], [[Bicolano people|Bicolano]] and [[Tagalog people|Tagalog]] migrants as early as 1870.<ref name=\"RomblonProv\"/>\n\n===Spanish period===\n[[File:Romblon circa 1905.JPG|left|thumb|The town of Romblon in the early 1900s, showing Fort San Andres in the background]]\n\nAccording to historians [[Emma Helen Blair]] and [[James Alexander Robertson]], the Spanish arrived in Romblon in 1569 led by [[conquistador]] [[Martin de Goiti]] who was dispatched by [[Miguel L\u00f3pez de Legazpi]] to explore the western and northern portion of the [[Visayas]] region including Romblon and Mindoro. The islands were later organized into three ''[[encomienda]]s'' and were administered from [[Iloilo province|Arevalo]]. De Loarca visited Romblon in 1582 and conducted the first census of the islands.<ref name=\"Loarca\"/>\n\nIn 1635, [[Recollects|Recollect missionaries]] arrived in Romblon to establish [[Catholic]] missions and settlements. They helped the Spanish authorities establish peace and order in the islands. In 1868, they established seven missionary centers at Romblon, Badajoz (San Agustin), Cajidiocan, Banton, Looc, Odiongan and Magallanes (Magdiwang). They also built massive forts, churches and watchtowers in the province, such as Fort San Jose in Banton and Fort San Andres in Romblon, following a Dutch attack in 1646 which destroyed the capital town and to repulse recurring Moro raids.<ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web |url=http://www.oocities.org/lppsec/pp/romblon.htm |title=Romblon: History |work=Philippine Provincial Profile |year=2000 |location=Manila: League of Provinces of the Philippines |accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"PSA\">{{cite web |url=https://psa4bromblon.files.wordpress.com/2013/08/romblon-profile.pdf |title=History |work=Profile of Romblon Province |location=Romblon: Philippine Statistical Authority |year=2013 |accessdate=8 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nRomblon was separated from the jurisdiction of Arevalo and annexed to [[Capiz province|Capiz]], when the province was created in 1716. More than a century later in 1850, the inhabitants of the province began using Spanish family names after [[Narciso Claver\u00eda y Zald\u00faa, 1st Count of Manila|governor-general Narciso Claver\u00eda]] decreed on 21 November 1849 the use of surnames from the ''[[Cat\u00e1logo alfab\u00e9tico de apellidos]]''. [[Asi language|Asi]]-speaking natives were assigned the letter F, Romblomanon speakers were assigned the letter M, speakers of the Sibuyanon style of Romblomanon were assigned the letter R, while [[Onhan language|Onhan]]-speaking natives were assigned the letter G.<ref name=\"Jernegan\">{{cite book |author=Jernegan, Prescott Ford |year=1905 |url=https://archive.org/details/ashorthistoryph00jerngoog |title=A short history of the Philippines: for use in Philippine schools |publisher=D. Appleton |pages=[https://archive.org/details/ashorthistoryph00jerngoog/page/n266 232]\u2013234 |location=New York: D. Appleton and Company}}</ref>\n\nIn 1853, the islands were organized into a politico-military ''commandancia'' (\"sub-province\" in English) administered from Capiz and continued to be so until the end of the Spanish rule in 1898.<ref name=\"Lancion\">{{cite book |author=Lancion, Conrado Jr. |year=1995 |title=Fast Facts About Philippine Provinces |location=Makati: Tahanan Books }}</ref> As a sub-province, Romblon was under an army officer with the rank of captain. The town of Romblon was its capital and the other municipalities were Azagra, Badajos (now San Agustin), Banton, Cajidiocan, Corcuera, Looc, Magallanes (now Magdiwang), Odiongan, Despujols (now San Andres) and Santa Fe.<ref name=\"PSA\"/>\n\n===Revolutionary period===\nIn 1898, amid the [[Philippine Revolution]], [[Katipunan]] leader [[Emilio Aguinaldo]] sent his generals to several provinces in the Visayas to expand the recognition of his revolutionary government in the central and southern Philippines.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/38519121|title=The Making of a Philippine Province: Romblon During the American Colonial Period|author=Kristoffer Esquejo|journal=Asian Stufies|volume=50|issue=2|year=2014}}</ref>The Katipunan general Mariano Riego de Dios and his forces liberated Romblon, while generals Ananias Diocno and Leandro Fullon proceeded to Panay. On 25 July the same year, Riego de Dios took the Romblon capital and captured Spanish officials.<ref name=Reyes1995p5658>{{Harvnb|Reyes|1995|pp=56\u201358}}</ref> Four days later, the Spanish politico-military governor Don Carlos Mendoza formally signed the surrender of Romblon's district government, ending more than three hundred years of Spanish rule in the archipelagic province.<ref name=Madeja1993p236>{{Harvnb|Madeja|1993|p=236}}</ref>\n\nLater, Don Wenceslao Molo, a local from Romblon town, was appointed governor and became responsible for the collection of a total amount of {{\u20b1|22,765.21|link=yes}}, Romblon's share to the war expenditures of the Revolutionary Government from 31 May 1898 to 28 February 1899. A local election was also held in Romblon town for its ministers of justice and barrio officials.<ref name=Reyes1995p54>{{Harvnb|Reyes|1995|p=54}}</ref> However, Molo's term was a brief transition to another era as the Americans arrived in the province a few months later.<ref name=\"Reyes1995p54\"/>\n\n===American period===\n[[File:Japanese battleship Musashi and a destroyer under attack in the Sibuyan Sea, 24 October 1944 (NH 63432).jpg|thumb|upright=1.0|The [[Japanese battleship Musashi|Japanese battleship ''Musashi'']] under fire during the [[Battle of Sibuyan Sea]] in 1944]]\n[[File:Sawang WW-II Plaque.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|A plaque in Barangay Sawang, [[Romblon, Romblon]], commemorating the liberation of the province from the Japanese during [[World War II]]]]\n\nUpon the restoration of peace and order in the province following the [[Philippine\u2013American War]], the Americans established civilian government in the islands on 16 March 1901. Romblon was created as a regular province in the same year but due to insufficient income, it became a sub-province of Capiz again in 1907 until 7 December 1917 when Act No. 2724 reestablished the province.<ref name=\"Fabella\">{{cite book |last=Fabella |first=Gabriel |year=1960 |title=Don Adriano N. Rios: Romblon's Patriarch. |work=Historical Bulletin 4 (3) |pages=67\u201368 |location=Manila: Philippine Historical Association |ref=harv}}</ref> Under Commonwealth Act No. 581, enacted without executive approval on 8 June 1940, the province was reorganized with four towns or municipalities, namely: Tablas (composed of [[Odiongan, Romblon|Odiongan]], [[Looc, Romblon|Looc]], and [[San Agustin, Romblon|Badajoz]]), Romblon (including the islands of Logbon, Cobrador and Alad), Maghali (comprising [[Banton, Romblon|Banton]], [[Corcuera, Romblon|Corcuera]], and [[Concepcion, Romblon|Concepcion]]), and Sibuyan (composed of the towns of [[Cajidiocan, Romblon|Cajidiocan]], [[Magdiwang, Romblon|Magdiwang]] and [[San Fernando, Romblon|San Fernando]]).<ref name=\"Esquejo\">{{cite book |title=The Making of a Philippine Province: Romblon During the American Colonial Period |author=Esquejo, Kristoffer |year=2014 |work=Asian Studies Journal |location=Manila: University of the Philippines-Diliman}}</ref><ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"Madeja1993p272\u2013273\">{{Harvnb|Madeja|1993|pp=272\u2013273}}</ref>\n\n===Japanese period===\nDuring [[World War II]], the [[Japanese Imperial Forces]] established a garrison in Romblon on 21 March 1942 which they maintained until the end of the war. The islands became one of the centers of [[Philippine resistance against Japan|resistance movement]] against the Japanese. The movement was led by the Free Panay Guerilla Forces composed of members from the 6th Military District under the direction of Col. Macario Peralta, Jr.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.ph/1989/07/21/proclamation-no-430-s-1989/ |title=Declaring the Eighteenth Day of March of every year as Victory Day in the Islands of Panay and Romblon, including the Cities of Iloilo and Roxas |work=Proclamation No. 430 |author=Aquino, Corazon |location=Manila: The Official Gazette |date=21 July 1989 |accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> One of the major naval engagements during the [[Battle of Leyte Gulf]], the [[Battle of Sibuyan Sea]], happened off the waters of Romblon on 23\u201324 October 1944  between Japanese [[Takeo Kurita|Admiral Kurita]]\u2019s fleet from [[Singapore]] and [[William Halsey, Jr.|Admiral Halsey]]'s carrier planes from the [[US Third Fleet]] then stationed east of the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.historyofwar.org/articles/battles_sibuyan_sea.html |title=Battle of the Sibuyan Sea, 23\u201324 October 1944 |author=Rickard, J. |date=3 May 2012 |publisher=HistoryofWar.org |accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref> Units from Company C of the 19th Infantry Regiment, 24th Infantry Division landed on Sawang, Romblon on the night 11 March 1945. By 18 March, the province was liberated from Japanese forces.<ref>{{cite book |author=Chant, Christopher |title=The Encyclopedia of Codenames of World War II |location=New York: Routledge Revivals |year=2013 |page=149}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Romblon Landing |work=Board Resolution No. 2 |year=1994 |location=Manila: National Historical Institute}}</ref>\n\n===Modern period===\nOn 1 October 1946, Congress passed Republic Act No. 38, sponsored by Cong. Modesto Formilleza, which abolished the four special municipalities and restored Romblon and its municipalities to its pre-war status.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://laws.chanrobles.com/republicacts/1_republicacts.php?id=38 |title=Republic Act No. 38 |work=An Act repealing Commonwealth Act numbered Five Hundred And Eighty-One, entitled, \"An Act abolishing the existing Municipal Governments and the Provincial Government of Romblon, and creating instead four Special Municipalities,\" restoring the regular Provincial Government and Municipalities of the Province of Romblon, and creating the Municipality of Santa Fe |publisher=Chan Robles Virtual Law Library |accessdate=22 October 2015}}</ref>  In the decades that followed, the province saw the creation of new municipalities, such as Alcantara (1961) from Looc, Calatrava (1969) from San Agustin, Ferrol (1978) from Odiongan, and Santa Maria (1984) from San Agustin.<ref name=\"Esquejo\"/>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Macat-ang Beach Banton.JPG|thumb|Macat-ang Beach in [[Banton, Romblon|Banton]]]]\nRomblon is strategically situated at the center of the Philippine [[archipelago]]. Geographically part of the [[Visayas]], it is composed of three major islands (Tablas, Sibuyan and Romblon) and 17 smaller islands. It is surrounded by deep waters, and is bounded by [[Masbate Island|Masbate]] in the east, [[Mindoro Island|Mindoro]] in the west, [[Marinduque Island|Marinduque]] in the north and Panay in the south. It is approximately {{convert|187|nmi|km|0}} and {{convert|169|mi|km|0}} south of Manila. The islands are dispersed and accessible only via sea transportation except for Tablas Island where a domestic airport is located in the municipality of Alcantara.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"NEDA\">{{cite web |url=http://mimaropa.neda.gov.ph/romblon/ |title=Location, Geography and Climate |work=Romblon Profile |location=Calapan City: National Economic and Development Authority (NEDA) MIMAROPA Region |accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Topography===\nThe province has a total land area of approximately {{convert|1,533.45|sqkm|sqmi|0}} representing about 5.3 percent of the total land area of Region IV-B [[Mimaropa]]. It is generally mountainous with about 40 percent of its land area having an inclination of more than 50 percent. Only four percent of the total area has an inclination of three to eight percent, while a sparse 10 percent has an inclination of three to zero percent. Narrow strips of coastal lowlands, low hills and plains typify the topography of some of the islands.<ref name=\"RomblonProv\"/><ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\">{{cite book |title=Geo-Physical Environment |work=Status Report on the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) using CBMS data |year=2010 |location=Romblon: Provincial Government of Romblon }}</ref>\n\nRomblon Island is hilly with a maximum elevation of about {{convert|400|m}} above sea level. Tablas Island shows varied relief characteristics. The western coastal areas are level to undulating while the eastern coastal areas are rough to rugged. The southern section covering Santa Fe and the mid-western portion may be described as having rolling to rough terrain. Extremely rugged areas can be found in the central section of the island. The highest elevation is almost {{convert|500|m}} above sea level. Sibuyan Island is a thickly forested mountain mass. The western portion of the island may be characterized as extensively rugged, having ascents of 60 percent or more while the eastern section is relatively undulating to rolling. The highest elevation, the peak of Mt. Guiting-Guiting, reaches about 2,058 meters (6,750 feet) above sea level.<ref name=\"RomblonProv\"/><ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/><ref name=G2>{{cite web |author=Lasco, Gideon | title=Mount Guiting-Guiting |date=26 March 2008 |publisher=Pinoy Mountaineer |url=http://www.pinoymountaineer.com/2008/03/mt-guiting-guiting-2058.html |accessdate=9 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe major areas that are highly productive and buildable are basically in Tablas and Sibuyan. These include Odiongan, San Andres, Looc and Santa Fe in Tablas Island. All three municipalities in Sibuyan Island, on the other hand, have substantial level to gently sloping lands. Overall, good developable lands represent about 13 percent of the province's total area.<ref name=\"RomblonProv\"/><ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n===Flora and fauna===\nRomblon, particularly Sibuyan Island, is among the few places in the Philippines with a well-preserved natural environment. Uninterrupted rainforest covers 75 percent of the island. It is also home to the country's cleanest inland body of water, the Cantigas River, as well as 34 waterfalls.<ref name=CP>{{cite web |url=http://www.choosephilippines.com/go/islands-and-beaches/46/galapagos-asia-sibuyan-island/ |author=Licap, Enzo |title=The Galapagos of Asia: Sibuyan Island |date=16 April 2013 |publisher=Choose Philippines |accessdate=2 May 2016}}</ref> Sibuyan is commonly known the country as the \"[[Galapagos]] of Asia\" because of its many [[endemic]] plant and animal species, some of which have just been discovered recently. Among these endemic species are nine mammals, seven lizards, two amphibians, three birds and 112 vascular plants,<ref name=CP/> such as the ''[[Nepenthes argentii]]'',<ref name=Nepenthes>{{cite book |author1=Jebb, M.H.P.  |author2=M.R. Cheek  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=1997 |title=A skeletal revision of Nepenthes (Nepenthaceae). |work=Blumea |pages=42(1): 1\u2013106}}</ref><ref name=McPherson>{{cite book |author=McPherson, S.R. |year=2009 |title=Pitcher Plants of the Old World (2 volumes) |publisher=Redfern Natural History Productions, Poole.}}</ref> ''[[Nepenthes sibuyanensis]]'',<ref name=Nepenthes/><ref name=McPherson/> ''[[Nepenthes armin]]'',<ref name=Nepenthes/><ref name=McPherson/> [[Sibuyan striped shrew rat]],<ref>{{cite book |author1=Rickart, E.A. |author2=Heaney, L.R. |author3=Goodman, S.M. |author4=Jansa, S. |year=2005 |title=Review of the Philippine genera Chrotomys and Celaenomys (Murinae) and description of a new species |work=Journal of Mammalogy |pages=86 (2): 415\u2013428}}</ref> [[Sibuyan shrew]],<ref>{{cite book |author1=Esselstyn, Jacob A. |author2=Goodman, Steven M. |year=2010 |title=New species of shrew (Soricidae: Crocidura) from Sibuyan Island, Philippines |work=Journal of Mammalogy |pages=91 (6): 1467\u20131472}}</ref> [[Philippine tube-nosed fruit bat]],<ref name=IUCN>{{Cite iucn | author = Ong, P. | author2 = Rosell-Ambal, G. | author3 = Tabaranza, B. | author4 = Heaney, L. | author5 = Ingle, N. | author6 = Cari\u00f1o, A.B. | author7 = Pangulatan, L.M. | author8 = Pedregosa, M. | author9 = Alcala, E. | author10 = Helgen, K. | last-author-amp = yes | title = ''Nyctimene rabori'' | volume = 2008 | page = e.T14953A4482609 | date = 2008 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T14953A4482609.en | access-date = 15 January 2018}}</ref> [[indigo-banded kingfisher]],<ref name=HBW>{{Citation|first=Peter|last=Woodall|editor-first=Josep|editor-last=del Hoyo|editor2-first=Andrew|editor2-last=Elliott|editor3-last=Sargatal|editor3-first=Jordi|contribution=Family Alcedinidae (Kingfishers)|title=Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 6, Mousebirds to Hornbills|year=2001|pages=[https://archive.org/details/handbookofbirdso0001unse/page/103 103\u2013187]|place=[[Barcelona]]|publisher=[[Lynx Edicions]]|isbn=978-84-87334-30-6|url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofbirdso0001unse/page/103}}</ref> and the [[Romblon hawk-owl]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Kennedy, R.S. |author2=Gonzales P.C. |author3=Dickinson E.C. |author4=Miranda Jr., H.C. |author5=Fisher T.H. |year=2000 |title=A Guide to the Birds of the Philippines |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford}}</ref> In Tablas Island, at least two endemic bird species can be found: the [[Tablas drongo]] and [[Tablas fantail]].<ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22736062/0 |title=''Dicrurus menagei'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2013 |access-date=2 March 2014|ref=harv}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=S\u00e1nchez-Gonz\u00e1lez, L.A. |author2=R.G. Moyle  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2011 |title=Molecular systematic and species limits in the Philippine fantails (Aves: Rhipidura) |work=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |pages=61: 290\u2013299}}</ref>\n\n===Administrative divisions===\nRomblon comprises 17 [[Philippine municipality|municipalities]]. Of these, nine are located in Tablas Island (San Agustin, Calatrava, San Andres, Odiongan, Ferrol, Santa Fe, Looc, Alcantara and Santa Maria), three in Sibuyan Island (Magdiwang, Cajidiocan and San Fernando) and five (Romblon, San Jose, Banton, Concepcion and Corcuera) are island municipalities.<ref name=\"RomblonProv\"/><ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"table-layout:fixed;text-align:right;background-color:white;font-size:95%;border-collapse:collapse;margin:auto;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"border-width:thin 0 0 thin;\" class=\"unsortable\" rowspan=\"2\" |\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"border-width:thin 0 0 0;text-align:left;padding-right:1.5em;\" class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"2\" | Municipality{{thinsp}}{{efn-lr|name=FormerName}}{{efn-lr|name=Coord}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"border-bottom:0;text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"3\" | Population\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"border-bottom:0;text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{PSGC rubric}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"border-bottom:0;text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"2\" | Area{{PSGC detail|nscb}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"border-bottom:0;text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\" colspan=\"2\" | Density{{thinsp}}{{small|(2015)}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"border-bottom:0;text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{abbr|Barangay|Total number of barangays}}\n|-\n! style=\"border-width:0 thin thin 0;\" colspan=\"2\" |\n! style=\"border-width:0 0 thin thin;text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\" | {{small|(2015)}}{{PH census|2015|04B}}\n! style=\"border-width:0 thin thin 0;text-align:center;\" | {{small|(2010)}}{{PH census|2010|04B}}\n! style=\"border-top:0;\" |\n! style=\"border-width:0 0 thin thin;text-align:center;\" | km<sup>2</sup>\n! style=\"border-width:0 thin thin 0;text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{nowrap|sq{{thinsp}}mi}}\n! style=\"border-width:0 0 thin thin;text-align:center;\" | /km<sup>2</sup>\n! style=\"border-width:0 thin thin 0;text-align:center;\" class=\"unsortable\" | {{nowrap|/sq{{thinsp}}mi}}\n! style=\"border-top:0;\" |\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"border-right:0;background-color:initial;\" | {{coord|12.2589|N|122.0534|E|name=Alcantara|region:PH-ROM_type:city|format=hidden}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-weight:bold;border-left:0;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Alcantara, Romblon|Alcantara]]\n| {{percent and number|16,351|292,781|disp=table|1|pad=yes}}\n| 15,428\n| {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|16,351|2010.3315|15,428}}\n| {{convert|60.12|km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| {{convert|{{sigfig|16,351/60.12|2}}|PD/km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 12\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"border-right:0;background-color:initial;\" | {{coord|12.9464|N|122.0945|E|name=Banton|region:PH-ROM_type:city|format=hidden}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-weight:bold;border-left:0;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Banton, Romblon|Banton]]&nbsp;{{small|(''Jones'')}}\n| {{percent and number|5,536|292,781|disp=table|1|pad=yes}}\n| 5,963\n| {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|5,536|2010.3315|5,963}}\n| {{convert|32.48|km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| {{convert|{{sigfig|5,536/32.48|2}}|PD/km2|abbr=values|disp=table}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 17\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"border-right:0;background-color:initial;\" | {{coord|12.3693|N|122.6862|E|name=Cajidiocan|region:PH-ROM_type:city|format=hidden}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;font-weight:bold;border-left:0;\" colspan=\"2\" | [[Cajidiocan, Romblon|Cajidiocan]]\n| {{percent and number|21,861|292,781|disp=table|1|pad=yes}}\n| 21,198\n| {{PAGR|color=true|2015.5835|21,861|2010.3315|21,198}}\n| {{convert|201.85|km2|