 Services Administration|PAGASA]]<ref name=PAGASAnormals>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181018045444/https://data.gov.ph/sites/default/files/pagasanormvalromblon1981-2010.csv\n| archivedate = 18 October 2018\n| url = https://data.gov.ph/?q=dataset/climatological-normal-values/resource/a146574e-4332-45b9-8c0f-e3b4a95aaccc\n| title = Romblon Climatological Normal Values\n| publisher = Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration\n| accessdate = 18 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=PAGASAextremes>\n{{cite web\n| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20181018045525/https://data.gov.ph/sites/default/files/pagasaclimextrromblon.csv\n| archivedate = 18 October 2018\n| url = https://data.gov.ph/?q=dataset/climatological-extremes/resource/ae1df0f6-4882-4830-9ff1-263b250d3da8\n| title = Romblon Climatological Extremes\n| publisher = Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration\n| accessdate = 18 October 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{Philippine Census\n| title    = Population census of<br />Romblon\n| 1903     = 52,848\n| 1918     = 64,610\n| 1939     = 99,367\n| 1948     = 108817\n| 1960     = 131658\n| 1970     = 167082\n| 1975     = 182209\n| 1980     = 193174\n| 1990     = 227621\n| 1995     = 244654\n| 2000     = 264357\n| 2007     = 279774\n| 2010     = 283930\n| 2015     = 292781\n| footnote = Source: Philippine Statistics Authority{{PH census|2015|04B}}{{PH census|2010|04B}}{{PH census|2010}}<ref name=\"NSOR4B-2007Census\">{{cite web|title=Fact Sheet; Region IV-B; MIMAROPA' 2007 Census of Population|url=http://www.nso-r4b.webs.com/special%20release/POPCEN%20Factsheet.pdf|website=Philippine Statistics Authority - Region IV-B|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n\n{{bar box\n| title    = Languages Spoken<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ethnologue.com/language/rol |title=Romblomanon |publisher=Ethnologue |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ethnologue.com/language/loc |title=Inonhan |publisher=Ethnologue |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ethnologue.com/language/bno |title=Bantoanon |publisher=Ethnologue |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref>\n| titlebar = #f99\n| left1    = Language\n| right1   = Population\n| float    = right\n| bars     =\n{{bar pixel|[[Romblomanon language|Romblomanon]]|Blue|36.89||94,000}}\n{{bar pixel|[[Onhan language|Onhan]]|Red|33.67||85,800}}\n{{bar pixel|[[Asi language|Asi]]|Yellow|29.43||75,000}}\n}}\n\nThe population of Romblon in the {{PH wikidata|population_as_of}} was {{PH wikidata|population_total}} people,{{PH census|current|04B}} with a density of {{convert|{{sigfig|{{PH wikidata|population_total}}/{{PH wikidata|area}}|2}}|PD/km2|disp=or}}. It ranks fourth among the five provinces of the MIMAROPA Region in terms of population and represents 9.9 percent of the region's population.\n\nSan Jose and Romblon are the two most-densely populated municipalities in the province at 490/km<sup>2</sup> and 450/km<sup>2</sup>, respectively. Cajidiocan is the least densely populated municipality at 110/km<sup>2</sup>.{{PH census|2015|04B}}\n\nMales outnumber females in the province with a sex ratio of 102:100 according to the 2010 census. Of the province's 283,482 household population, males accounted for 144,091 or 50.8 percent while females made up 139,391 or 49.2 percent. The voting-age population (18 years old and over) accounted for 56.6 percent of the household population of the province in 2010, up from 52.7 percent in 2000. There were more females (50.2 percent) than males (49.8 percent) among the voting age population.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n===Language===\n{{main|Romblomanon language|Onhan language|Asi language}}\n\nThe languages of Romblon, as well as all languages native to the Philippines, belong to the [[Austronesian languages|Austronesian language family]], the second largest language family in the world with 1,257 known languages, second only to the [[Niger-Congo languages|Niger-Congo family's]] 1,538 languages. All of the languages of the Philippines, except Samalan, are classified as Philippine languages under the [[Western Malayo-Polynesian languages|Western Malayo-Polynesian]] branch of Austronesian. The Philippine language group has three main branches: [[Philippine languages|Northern]], [[Mindanao languages|Southern]] and [[Central Philippine languages|Central]], the latter of which is composed of the [[Visayan languages|Visayan]], [[Bikol languages|Bikol]] and [[Tagalog language]]s.<ref name=Language>{{cite web |url=http://sanrokan.com/newsanrokan/archives/jul8/feature_lobel.htm |title=''An Introduction to the Languages of Romblon Province'' |first=Jason William |last=Lobel |date=8 July 2002 |publisher=Sanrokan News Magazine |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=Lobel>{{cite web |url=http://www.ling.hawaii.edu/graduate/Dissertations/JasonLobelFinal.pdf |title=Philippine and North Bornean languages: issues in description, subgrouping, and reconstruction''. |publisher=University of Hawai'i at Manoa |location=Manoa |year=2013 |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnlike other islands or provinces in the Philippines where all local languages are classifiable under the same subgroup of languages, each of the three languages of Romblon \u2014 Romblomanon, Onhan and Asi \u2014 actually belongs to a different subgroup of the Visayan language group. Romblomanon belongs to the Central Visayan subgroup, which spans from [[Waray language|Waray-Waray]] in [[Samar]] and [[Leyte]], through [[Masbatenyo language|Masbatenyo]] and [[Bisakol languages|Bisakol]], and as far west as [[Hiligaynon language|Hiligaynon]] and [[Capiznon]] on [[Panay]]. It is spoken in Romblon and Sibuyan Islands, as well as in San Agustin town in Tablas Island.<ref name=Language/><ref name=Lobel/>\n\nOnhan, on the other hand, belongs to the Western Visayan subgroup, which includes [[Kinaray-a]] and [[Aklanon language|Aklanon]] as well as several minor languages spoken on Mindoro, Palawan, and some small islands in between. Its speakers are mainly from the southern portion of Tablas Island, in the municipalities of San Andres, Santa Maria, Alcantara, Ferrol, Looc, and Santa Fe, as well as in the municipality of San Jose in Carabao Island.<ref name=Language/> Finally, Asi is not classified under any specific subgroup of Visayan, and instead makes up its own immediate branch of Visayan.<ref name=Language/><ref name=Lobel/> David Paul Zorc, a [[linguist]] from the [[Australian National University]] whose expertise is on Philippine languages, notes that Asi speakers may have been the first Visayan speakers in the region. He also suggests that Asi may have a [[Cebuano language|Cebuano]] [[substratum]] and that many of its words may have been influenced by the later influx of other languages such as Romblomanon.<ref name=\"Zorc\">Zorc, R. David Paul. (1977)</ref> It is spoken in the island municipalities of Banton, Corcuera and Concepcion, as well as in Odiongan and Calatrava in Tablas.<ref name=Language/> Hiligaynon is spoken in municipalities near Capiz and Aklan.\n\n===Religion===\nThe people of the province are predominantly [[Roman Catholic]]. In 2012, the [[UP School of Economics]] reported that in recent years, 69 percent were [[Catholics]], 30 percent belong to [[Iglesia Filipina Independiente]] while five percent to [[Muslim]]s, and around three percent belonged to [[Iglesia ni Cristo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.econ.upd.edu.ph/dp/index.php/dp/article/viewFile/692/159|title=Discussion Paper No. 2012-09 : Are improved water supply and sanitation always safe for children? Implications for attaining the MDGs in the Philippines.|author1=Joseph J. Capuno|author2=Carlos Antonio R. Tan Jr|publisher=School of Economics, University of the Philippines|page=11}}</ref> Other Christian groups such as Iglesia Filipina Independiente then [[Mainline Protestant]] and [[Evangelicalism|Evangelicals]] form a significant minority of up to 8% of the population.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://philchal.org/dawn/provinceupdates/ProvSum_%20ROMBLON_2011.pdf|title=Province Summary - Romblon 2011|publisher=philchal.org}}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Abaca weaving in Banton.JPG|thumb|upright=1.0|left|[[Abac\u00e1#Textiles|Abac\u00e1 weaving]] in Banton]]\n\n===Agriculture===\nAgriculture is the main industry in Romblon. [[Coconut]] is the most cultivated crop with a total planted area of {{convert|58,270.44|ha|sqmi}}. San Agustin has the most extensive area with coconut plants followed by Romblon and Cajidiocan. [[Rice]] is the next crop, cultivated particularly in Odiongan, Looc, Cajidiocan and Santa Fe. Other crops grown include root crops, vegetables and fruits. Odiongan, Banton and Magdiwang have the greatest areas planted with root crops and correspondingly, have the highest volume of production. Vegetable production is mostly for home consumption and grown in small scale.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n[[File:Fishing in Romblon.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Fisherfolk in Romblon unload the day's catch from their nets.]]\n\n[[Livestock]] development and [[poultry]] production is a viable small scale enterprise for farmers in the province. The provincial government maintains breeding facilities in strategic locations province-wide to encourage farmers to engage in livestock and poultry production to augment their income. Livestock and poultry management training and seminars is provided to interested clients.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\nDue to the geographical condition of the province, crops and livestock production is generally deficient as compared to the food requirements of Romblon population. To meet the rice requirements, Romblon relies on imports from the neighboring provinces while vegetables, poultry meat, vegetables and fruits are supplied mostly by Luzon.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n===Marine resources===\n[[Fishing]] industry is a major enterprise as Romblon is surrounded by water on all sides. The fishing grounds of Romblon are a migratory path of fish from [[Sulu Sea|Sulu]] and [[Visayan Sea]]s passing [[Tablas Strait]], [[Sibuyan Sea]] and Romblon Pass. The waters also abound with [[demersal fish]] due to the coral reefs surrounding the islands.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\nBecause the province has a great potential for aqua-marine development, the province implemented a coastal and resource management program. Each municipality established a [[marine protected area|fish sanctuary]] and passed laws on fishery. The use of [[air compressors]] in the [[territorial waters|municipal waters]] was regulated and banned altogether in some municipalities.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n===Mineral resources===\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    =\n | width     = 180\n | image1    = romblon island 089col.jpg\n | alt1      =\n | caption1  = Marble wares from Romblon\n | image2    = Romblon Marble plant workers.jpg\n | alt2      =\n | caption2  = Marble plant workers working in a quarry.\n | align     = right\n}}\n\nMarble is the most significant mineral deposit of Romblon and is the most renowned product of the province. Based on statistics, Romblon is the second biggest provincial marble producer of the country next to [[Bulacan (province)|Bulacan]]. Romblon marble is of very high quality and comes in shades of white, green, pink, red and black. The [[Mines and Geosciences Bureau]] has estimated that Romblon is endowed with about 150 million metric tons of marble. At current rates of extraction, the supply may last for three more centuries. Tablas Island is also believed to have vast reserves of marble.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\nMarble quarrying and processing are major activities in Romblon. Among the most common marble products are categorized into the following: novelty items (gifts, ashtray, table bars), furniture (dining tables, baptismal fonts) and construction materials (tiles, balusters, marble chips). Other mineral resources with considerable quantity include [[nickel]] ore and [[gold]] mostly to be found in Sibuyan Island. [[Gold panning]] and [[Artisanal mining|small-scale mining]] is a lucrative undertaking in Magdiwang.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:Tambak Beach.JPG|thumb|Tambak Beach in Banton]]\n[[File:Tabunan Beach with Kayak.jpg|thumb|Tabunan Beach in Banton]]\n[[File:Banton Burial Cloth.JPG|thumb|The Banton Cloth, the oldest existing example of warp [[ikat]] in Southeast Asia, displayed at the [[National Museum of the Philippines]].]]\n\n===Natural attractions===\nBeing an archipelago, Romblon has numerous beaches and dive sites. Among its best white sand beaches are Bonbon, Cobrador and Tiamban Beach in Romblon, Macat-ang, Tabunan and Tambak Beach in Banton, Lunas and Bignay Beach in San Jose, and Cresta del Gallo in San Fernando.<ref name=Epi>{{cite web |url=http://tourism-philippines.com/banton-island/ |title=Banton Island |first=Epi |last=Fabonan III |date=29 May 2009 |publisher=Tourism Philippines |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=Lakwatsero>{{cite web |url=http://www.lakwatsero.com/spots/the-beaches-of-romblon-island/ |title=The Beaches of Romblon |date=17 October 2013 |publisher=Lakwatsero |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=OutofTown>{{cite web |url=http://outoftownblog.com/top-8-things-to-do-and-see-in-romblon/ |title=Top 8 Things to do and see in Romblon |first=Melo |last=Villareal |date=13 June 2014 |publisher=Out of Town Blog |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> The sea surrounding Cresta del Gallo is a famous diving site teeming with marine life.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://divescover.com/dive-site/cresta-de-gallo/40629 |title=Cresta de Gallo |publisher=Divescover |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> Romblon is also home to the only known [[blue hole]] in the Philippines in the town of San Agustin.<ref name=BlueHole1>{{cite web |url=http://www.lakwatsero.com/dive-report/scuba-diving-in-romblon-blue-hole-and-gorda-wall/ |title=Scuba Diving in Romblon: Blue Hole and Gorda Wall |date=18 February 2015 |publisher=Lakwatsero |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=BlueHole2>{{cite web |url=http://www.justgottadive.com/dive_resources/travel_articles/seven-spectacular-romblon-dive-sites-blue-hole-giant-clam-sanctuary#.VvtmMRN97Sw |title=Seven Spectacular Romblon Dive Sites: From Blue Hole To The Giant Clam Sanctuary |first=Melissa |last=Gwaldis |publisher=JustGottaDive.com |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> The entrance to the blue hole is a {{convert|6|m|adj=on}} wide volcanic chimney, which drops for {{convert|20|m}} before opening up into the massive chamber below with a total depth of {{convert|32|to(-)|40|m}}.<ref name=BlueHole2/>\n\nMount Guiting-Guiting in Sibuyan, the province's tallest mountain, is considered as one of the most difficult climbs in the Philippines, and is thus a major destination of local mountain climbers because of its steep and jagged summit.<ref name=G2/> Another a suitable place for hiking and trekking is Mount Payaopao is Tablas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://visitromblon.blogspot.com/2014/08/mount-payaopao.html |title=Mount Payaopao |publisher=Visit Romblon |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, Banton's Guyangan Cave System, an Important Cultural Treasure, is where the Banton Cloth \u2014 the earliest known warp ''[[ikat]]'' textile in Southeast Asia \u2014 was found in 1936.<ref name=\"Ikat\">{{cite news |url=http://opinion.inquirer.net/15599/history-and-design-in-death-blankets |title=Looking Back: History and design in Death Blankets |first=Ambeth |last=Ocampo |date=19 October 2011 |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.filipiknow.net/archaeological-discoveries-in-the-philippines/ |title=15 Most Intense Archaeological Discoveries in Philippine History |first=Luisito |last=Batongbakal Jr. |publisher=Filipiknow.net |accessdate=14 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalmuseum.gov.ph/nationalmuseumbeta/Collections/Archaeo/Banton.html |title=Collections: Banton Cloth |publisher=[[National Museum of the Philippines]] |accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:MainitFalls81027cgb.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|left|Mainit Falls in Odiongan]]\n\n===Heritage sites===\nAside from the precolonial Guyangan Cave System in Banton, the province also has several heritage sites built during the Spanish colonial period. In Romblon town, the forts of San Andres and Santiago served as fortifications against Muslim pirates in the 17th century, while the St. Joseph Cathedral and Belfry houses a centuries-old image of the [[Santo Ni\u00f1o de Ceb\u00fa]] or the Holy Child.<ref name=FortRomblon>{{cite web |url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/105261/romblon-cathedral-ancient-hispanic-forts-declared-national-cultural-treasures |title=Romblon cathedral, ancient Hispanic forts declared National Cultural Treasures |first=Levine Andro |last=Lao |date=26 May 2013 |publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer |location=Manila |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> Both heritage sites were declared National Cultural Treasures by the National Museum.<ref name=FortRomblon/> The town also has two Spanish-era bridges that were declared Important Cultural Treasures.<ref name=FortRomblon/> A similar fort in Banton, the centuries-old Fort San Jose and [[Banton Church]], were built in the 1600s and was also used as defenses against Muslim pirates.<ref name=Banton/>\n\n===Festivals===\nEvery second week of January, Romblon town celebrates the feast of the Santo Ni\u00f1o de Ceb\u00fa, also known as the Biniray Festival.<ref name=Biniray>{{cite web |url=http://www.wowromblon.com/features/enjoy-the-biniray-festival-of-romblon/ |title=Biniray Festival Features Romblomanon's Faith to Patron Santo Nino |date=13 December 2012 |publisher=Wow Romblon |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> In that week, a fluvial parade featuring the image of the Santo Ni\u00f1o goes around Romblon Bay in order to bring good luck to the villages.<ref name=Biniray/> A [[mardi gras]] is also held in the town with various street dancing, food, drinks and music.<ref name=Biniray/> A similar Biniray Festival also occurs in Banton every 10 September in commemoration of the island's patron, [[Nicholas of Tolentino|San Nicolas de Tolentino]].<ref name=\"Profile\"/> Other festivals include the Saginyogan Festival in Alcantara,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alcantararomblon.weebly.com/the-saginyogan-festival.html |title=The Saginyongan Festival |first=Nancy |last=Lota |publisher=The Official Website of Alcantara, Romblon |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> the Sanrokan Festival in Banton,<ref name=\"Profile\"/> and the [[Talabukon Festival]] in Looc.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wowromblon.com/features/festivals/do-you-believe-in-genies-join-the-talabukon-festival/ |title=Do you believe in genies? Join the Talabukon Festival in Looc, Romblon! |date=14 December 2012 |publisher=Wow Romblon |accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Brlm8CZEsIcC&lpg=PA267&dq=talabukon+festival&pg=PA267#v=onepage&q=talabukon%20festival&f=false |title=Philippines, ebook Edition |first=Greg |last=Bloom |publisher=Lonely Planet |year=2009 |accessdate=30 March 2016|isbn=9781742203706 }}</ref>\n\n=== Scuba diving ===\nIn recent years Romblon Island has attracted more scuba divers. It has pristine and untouched reefs with almost undisturbed hard and soft corals around the islands of Romblon, Logbon, Alad and Cobrador. With multiple marine sanctuaries and private associations most of the marine life around Romblon is protected. In addition to the reefs, Romblon has been becoming famous for its rare and unique macro habitat, such as the ''[[Melibe]] colemani'', the ''[[Cyerce]] nigra'' and the ''Cyerce bourbonica''.\n\n==Government==\n\n===Executive===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:1.7em;margin-top:0;text-align:center;\" align=right\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Provincial Government of Romblon<br />{{small|(2019\u20132022)}}\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Legislative district of Romblon|Representative]]\n|- \n| colspan=\"2\" | Eleandro Jesus Madrona<br />({{small|[[Nacionalista Party]]}})\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[Governor of Romblon|Governor]] \n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | Jose Riano<br />({{small|[[PDP-Laban]]}})\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Vice Governor\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | Felix Ylagan<br />({{small|[[Lakas-CMD|LAKAS]]}})\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Provincial Board Members\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold;\"\n| First District || Second District\n|-\n| Nene Solis || Fred Dorado\n|-\n| Rachel Ba\u00f1ares || Robert Maulion\n|-\n| Jun Bernardo || DJ Bing Solis\n|-\n| Guds Mortel || Jose Madrid\n|}\n\n{{main|Governor of Romblon}}\n\nJust like any other province in the Philippines, Romblon's chief executive and head is the provincial governor.<ref name=\"Gov\">{{cite web |url=http://www.lawphil.net/statutes/repacts/ra1991/ra_7160_1991.html |title=An Act Providing for a Local Government Code of 1991 |publisher=8th Congress of the Republic of the Philippines |accessdate=April 21, 2014}}</ref> Elected to a term of three years and limited to three consecutive terms, he or she appoints the directors of each provincial department, which include the office of administration, engineering office, information office, legal office, and treasury office.<ref name=\"Gov\"/> As of 30 June 2019, the incumbent governor of Romblon is Jose \"Otik\" Riano, from the [[PDP\u2013Laban|PDPLBN]]. He was [[Philippine gubernatorial elections, 2013|elected in 2013]] as vice-governor and reelected in 2016.<ref name=\"COMELEC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.comelec.gov.ph/?r=Archives/RegularElections/2013NLE/Results/prov2013 |title=Provincial Election Results: Romblon |work=May 13, 2013 National and Local Elections |date=12 May 2014 |location=Manila: Commission on Elections |accessdate=18 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe provincial vice governor performs duties as acting governor in the absence of the provincial governor.<ref name=\"Gov\"/> He or she also automatically succeeds as governor upon the death of the provincial governor.<ref name=\"Gov\"/> The provincial vice governor also convenes the [[Romblon Provincial Board|Provincial Board]] or ''[[Sangguniang Panlalawigan]]'', the provincial legislative body.<ref name=\"Gov\"/> The incumbent provincial vice governor of Romblon is Felix Ylagan from the [[Lakas\u2013CMD|LAKAS]]. He is a grandson of the late governor of the same province, Perpetuo Ylagan.\n\n===Legislative===\n{{main|Legislative district of Romblon|Romblon Provincial Board}}\n\nThe province, which is a lone congressional district, is represented in the [[Philippine House of Representatives]] by longtime [[Congress of the Philippines|congressman]] Eleandro Jesus \"Budoy\" Madrona from the [[Nacionalista Party]].<ref name=\"COMELEC2\"/> He first assumed office from 1992 to 2001, serving three terms. Following two terms wherein Perpetuo Ylagan and Eduardo Firmalo respectively represented the district in Congress, Madrona ran and won again in 2007. His third and last term will expire in 2016.<ref name=\"COMELEC2\"/>\n\nWithin the province, the Provincial Board or ''Sangguniang Panlalawigan'' crafts all provincial ordinances, performs appropriation of provincial funds, issues franchises and permits, impose fees on provincial services, and exercise other duties and powers as stipulated by the Local Government Code of 1991.<ref name=\"Gov\"/> Romblon, being a third-class province in terms of income, is entitled to a Provincial Board composed of eight members, four each from the province's two board districts.<ref name=\"Gov\"/> {{As of|2013}}, the incumbent board members from the province's two districts are: (First District) Samuel Romero, Anthony Rugas, Abner Perez, Nelson Lim ; (Second District) Felix Ylagan, Juliet Fiel, Venizar Maravilla, and Andres Fondevilla.<ref name=\"COMELEC\"/>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n[[File:Poctoy Pier 2014.jpg|upright=1.0|thumb|Poctoy Pier in [[Odiongan]], the largest port in Romblon province]]\n\nRomblon province is connected by a network of national and provincial roads. National roads form much of this network, with a total length of {{convert|311.046|km}}. Provincial roads, meanwhile, total {{convert|239.005|km}} in length. Municipal and [[barangay]] roads in far-flung villages and island municipalities are not part of these figures. The primary modes of land transportation in the province are [[jeepney]]s, [[motorcycle taxi|passenger motorcycles]], [[minibus]]es and [[motorized tricycle (Philippines)|tricycle]]s that serve inter-municipal movements and linkages.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\nSea transportation is the primary mode of transportation linking Romblon with Luzon and islands in the Visayas. Inter-island ferries, [[RORO]], and cargo ships from Manila, the southern Luzon ports of [[Batangas City]], [[Lucena, Philippines|Lucena City]] in [[Quezon province]], [[Roxas, Oriental Mindoro]], and [[Roxas City]] in Capiz province are the primary modes of transportation linking the province to the rest of the country. [[Montenegro Lines]], [[2GO]], and Romblon Shipping Lines all have ferry service from Manila to the main ports of entry of [[Odiongan]] and the capital town of Romblon and vice versa. From Romblon, Montenegro also serves Magdiwang in Sibuyan, while Romblon Shipping Lines also serves [[Cajidiocan]].<ref name=\"MSL\">{{cite web |url=http://www.montenegrolines.com.ph/index.php?nav=4 |title=Trips |publisher=Montenegro Shipping Lines |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"RSL\">{{cite web |url=http://www.romblonshippinglines.com/destinations/ |title=Destinations |publisher=Romblon Shipping Lines |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> [[Pump boats]] and wooden launches also link the province to the towns of [[Buenavista, Marinduque]] and [[Pinamalayan, Oriental Mindoro]]. These pump boats are also used in going to barangays where there are no existing road networks or between municipalities in the province that do not have existing ferry service.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n[[Tugdan Airport]] in Alcantara is the only airport in the province and is less than an hour away from Metro Manila. [[Philippine Airlines]], the country's flag carrier, used to fly thrice a week (Sunday, Wednesday and Friday<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philippineairlines.com/files/5714/4945/8048/Domestic_Winter_Schedule_Dec_03_2015_1.pdf|page=3|title=Domestic Winter Schedule Effective October 25 2015 until March 26, 2016|publisher=Philippines Airlines|accessdate=2015-12-10}}</ref>)  to the airport via its budget carrier, [[PAL Express]],<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philippineairlines.com/news-and-events/pal-advises-passengers-come-airport-early-27/ |title=PAL opens Manila-Tablas service |publisher=Philippine Airlines |date=20 March 2015 |accessdate=17 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150828054029/http://www.philippineairlines.com/news-and-events/pal-advises-passengers-come-airport-early-27/ |archivedate=August 28, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.manilatimes.net/pal-bares-new-domestic-routes/167442/ |title=PAL bares new domestic routes |first=Benjie |last=Vergara |publisher=The Manila Times |date=5 March 2015 |accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref> but has ceased as of 1 September 2016 due to transfer of some of its flights to [[Clark International Airport]] in [[Pampanga]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bworldonline.com/content.php?section=Corporate&title=pal-cancels-29-flights-plans-to-operate-new-routes-from-clark&id=132771 |title=PAL cancels 29 flights, plans to operate new routes from Clark |first=Hernandez |last=Monica |publisher=[[BusinessWorld]] |date=1 September 2016|accessdate=13 March 2017}}</ref> Currently, only [[Cebu Pacific]] has flights to the airport, with four flights weekly from Manila.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/02/15/17/cebu-pacific-launches-masbate-romblon-flights |title=Cebu Pacific launches Masbate, Romblon flights |publisher=[[ABS-CBN]] |date=15 February 2017}}</ref> At Barangay Azagra, San Fernando in Sibuyan Island, there is also a small airstrip that caters to tourism and general aviation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.pia.gov.ph/article/view/2161424915162/tagalog-news-sibuyan-island-sa-romblon-planong-lagyan-ng-airport |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105090657/http://news.pia.gov.ph/article/view/2161424915162/tagalog-news-sibuyan-island-sa-romblon-planong-lagyan-ng-airport|archivedate=2016-01-05 |title=Sibuyan Island sa Romblon planong lagyan ng airport |author=Manzo, Dinnes |date=27 February 2015 |publisher=Philippine Information Agency |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Electricity===\nPower supply in Romblon is generated by the National Power Corporation (NPC) and serviced by two electric cooperatives. Tablas Island Electric Cooperatives (TIELCO) serves the power needs of Tablas Island including San Jose. It operates a 5.070 MW diesel power plant in Odiongan and 1.740 MW power barge in San Agustin.<ref name=\"SPUG\">{{cite web |url=http://www.spug.ph/MEP%202012-2021/MEP%202012-2021%20LUZON%20AREA/MEP%202012-2021%20ROMBLON.pdf |title=Missionary Electrification Plan (2012\u20132021) |publisher=Small Power Utilities Group, National Power Corporation |year=2011 |accessdate=17 August 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105090657/http://www.spug.ph/MEP%202012-2021/MEP%202012-2021%20LUZON%20AREA/MEP%202012-2021%20ROMBLON.pdf |archivedate=5 January 2016 }}</ref> The electric cooperative serves a total of 21,097 house connections.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/> In 2013, TIELCO has entered into a 15-year power supply agreement with Sunwest Water and Electric Company (SUWECO) to fill the island's energy needs. In 2015, SUWECO opened a diesel power plant in Barangay Batiano, Odiongan, which supplies TIELCO with 8.8 MW of electricity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bworldonline.com/content.php?section=Corporate&title=tiny-energy-player-to-power-off-grid-island-in-romblon&id=110190|title=Tiny energy player to power off-grid island in Romblon|first=Claire-Ann Marie|last=Feliciano|date=24 June 2015|publisher=[[BusinessWorld]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> In 2019, TIELCO and SUWECO inaugurated the 7.5 MW peak Tumingad Solar Power Plant in Odiongan. The two power plants address the power problem of the towns of Odiongan, San Andres, Calatrava, San Agustin, Santa Maria, Santa Fe, Alcantara, Looc, and Ferrol in Tablas.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1026210|title=PRRD leads inauguration of the 7.5MWp solar power plant in Romblon|first=Paul Jaysent|last=Fos|date=23 August 2019|publisher=[[Philippine Information Agency]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> Likewise, TIELCO supplies electricity to San Jose and has recently held the bidding for the competitive selection process (CSP) for a new power provider to the island municipality.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2019/05/31/1922233/carabao-island-seeks-power-supply-offers|title=Carabao Island seeks power supply offers|first=Danessa|last=Rivera|publisher=[[The Philippine Star]]|date=31 May 2019|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nRomblon Electric Cooperative (ROMELCO) supplies the capital town of Romblon through a 1.720 MW diesel power plant and a 1.30 MW power barge. It also serves Sibuyan Island using a 3.006 MW diesel power plant in San Fernando.<ref name=\"SPUG\"/> ROMELCO has 5,288 house connections in Romblon and 5,150 house connections in the three municipalities located in Sibuyan Island or a total of 10,438 house connections in their franchise area. Additionally, ROMELCO installed in 2010 a [[small hydro|mini hydro]] power plant in Cantigas, San Fernando, producing 900&nbsp;kW of power.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.napocor.gov.ph/website_contents/2013_major_programs/2013_accomplishments.pdf |title=2013 Accomplishment Report |publisher=Small Power Utilities Group, National Power Corporation |accessdate=15 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304105353/http://www.napocor.gov.ph/website_contents/2013_major_programs/2013_accomplishments.pdf |archivedate=4 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.devbnkphl.com/news.php?id=23 |title=DBP-funded mini-hydro plant to provide electricity in Romblon |publisher=Development Bank of the Philippines |date=11 March 2010 |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/news/feature/2011/03/18/philippines-hydro-power-injects-diversity-sibuyan-islands-economy |title=Hydro Power Injects Diversity Into Sibuyan Island's Economy |publisher=World Bank |date=18 March 2011 |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> In 2019, ROMELCO also installed three 300-kW wind turbines in Barangays Agnay, Bagacay and Lonos in Romblon, Romblon with a combined capacity to generate 2,000,100 kilowatt hours of green energy, or equivalent to 25 percent of the total annual energy requirement of the island. The 42-meter tall wind turbines were manufactured by Japanese company Komaihaltec Inc. and supported by the [[Ministry of the Environment (Japan)|Ministry of the Environment of Japan]]. An additional 900-kW wind turbines will be installed in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2019/02/14/romblon-goes-for-green-power-with-launch-of-3-wind-turbines/|title=Romblon goes for green power with launch of 3 wind turbines|first=Lenie|last=Lectura|date=14 February 2019|publisher=[[BusinessMirror]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1070366/romblon-taps-wind-for-cleaner-cheaper-electricity|title=Romblon taps wind for cleaner, cheaper electricity|first=Maricar|last=Cinco|date=8 January 2019|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref> ROMELCO also provides 24-hour electricity to the island municipalities of Banton, Concepcion and Corcuera through diesel power plants operated by the NPC.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/> \n\n===Water supply===\n[[File:Banton Spanish-era well.JPG|upright=1.0|thumb|A Spanish-era well in [[Banton, Romblon|Banton]]]]\n\nOut of 17 municipalities, 14 have Level III [[water supply]] systems serving 18,590 households or about 32.57 percent of the total provincial households. Level III has a [[reservoir]] with house-to-house connections. 5,252 households were serviced by Level II water systems and 24,700 households by Level I water system. Level I category is a common facility where the community members get their water supply from [[Artesian aquifer|deep wells]] and [[Water well|shallow wells]], while Level II has a reservoir with communal faucet. Based on the report from the Provincial Health Office in 2007, a total of 48,542 households out of the 57,079 or 85.04 percent have access to safe [[drinking water]].<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n===Telecommunications===\nThe province has several operating telecommunication exchanges, namely Kayumanggi, Romblontel, Odiongan Telephone Corporation (OTELCO), the\nTelecommunication Office (TELOF), telegram system, [[Vega Telecom|Liberty Telecom]], public calling stations under the [[Department of Transportation and Communications (Philippines)|DOTC]] and the Provincial Communication System (PCS) radio transceivers and receivers. [[Smart Communications]], [[Sun Cellular]] and [[Globe Telecom]] already have relay stations in Romblon, Odiongan and Cajidiocan, enabling most areas province-wide connected through [[cellphones]], except on some area where the signal is weak or non-existent because of mountains that block the signal. The Triple Peak in Santa Maria has a relay station for [[PLDT]] and Liberty Telecom.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n==Media==\nThere are three radio stations in the province, two of which are operated by the [[Radyo Natin Network]] and the other, Charm FM 100.5&nbsp;MHz, by the Polytechnic Foundation of Cotabato and Asia. Radyo Natin Network operates the call sign DWMM at 104.5&nbsp;MHz on [[FM broadcasting|FM radio]] from Looc, as well as the call sign DZVG 101.3&nbsp;MHz on [[FM broadcasting|FM radio]] from Odiongan.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ntcr4.com/fm-radioseven.html |title=List of Existing Radio and TV Stations |publisher=National Telecommunications Commission \u2013 Region IV-B |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.radyonatin.com/story.php?storyid=6584 |title=List of Radyo Natin FM Stations |publisher=Radyo Nation Network |accessdate=15 September 2015}}</ref> As for print media, ''Romblon Text'' and ''Romblon Sun'' are the two major newspapers circulating in the province, aside from broadsheet and tabloid newspapers from Manila.<ref name=\"PSA\"/> ''Romblon News'', meanwhile, provides provincial and national news and information via [[the web]] and [[social media]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://romblonnews.net/index.php/2-site-info/34-about-us |title=About Us |publisher=Romblon News |accessdate=16 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nA relay station for [[GMA Network]] and Romblon Community TV (affiliate of [[People's Television Network]]) in Santa Maria allows the province to access television shows broadcast by the network from Manila. There are also existing cable providers and local cable stations operating in several municipalities in the province, namely Romblon Cable Corporation (Romblon), Accutronics System Inc. (Odiongan), San Agustin Cable Antenna Corp. (San Agustin), Countryside Satellite Television System Inc. (Looc), Gateway Cable TV Network (Calatrava), San Andres CATV Service Coop. (San Andres), Josefa J. Martinez CATV Services (Alcantara), Magdiwang Cable Television (Magdiwang), and Sibuyan Cable TV (San Fernando and Cajidiocan). Aside from these cable stations, there are also distributors of direct-to-home (DTH) satellite TV such as [[Cignal Digital TV]], [[Dream Satellite TV]], [[G Sat]], and [[Sky Direct]] who provide television services for its subscribers.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/>\n\n==Education==\nThe Division of Romblon of the [[Department of Education]] (DepEd) supervises and oversees the delivery of education and operations of public schools in the province. It is composed of 13 districts, where there are 228 elementary schools, 216 of which are public and 12 are private. Of the 216 public elementary schools, 162 offer preschool education, while 20 of the private schools have the same offering. There are also 10 private preschools offering pre-elementary. For secondary level, a total of 44 schools offer secondary education, of which 37 are public schools and seven are private institutions. The [[Virginia Centurione Bracelli School]] offers both primary and secondary education. There are 13 [[vocational school]]s in the province, while [[tertiary education]] is offered by privately owned [[Romblon College]] and the [[Romblon State University]] (RSU), one of the oldest state universities in the Philippines.<ref name=\"PSA\"/><ref name=\"MDG\"/> RSU, which was founded in 1915, is the oldest agricultural university in the Philippines and has campuses in Romblon, Odiongan, Cajidiocan, Calatrava, San Agustin, San Andres, San Fernando, Santa Fe, and Santa Maria.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsu.edu.ph/AboutUs/History/102 |title=History |publisher=Romblon State University |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsu.edu.ph/AboutUs/Campuses/116 |title=Campuses |publisher=Romblon State University |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\n{{multiple image\n | direction = vertical\n | footer    =\n | width     = 100\n | image1    = Gabriel_Fabella.jpg\n | alt1      =\n | caption1  = Historian Gabriel Fabella\n | image4    = Rodne_Galicha,_young_Philippine_environment_activist.jpg\n | alt4      =\n | caption4  = Environmental activist Rodne Galicha\n | align     = right\n}}\n* [[Fitch Arboleda]], [[Filipino people|Filipino]] footballer who plays for [[Stallion F.C.|Stallion FC]] and the [[Philippines national football team]].\n* [[Florante Condes]], [[Filipino people|Filipino]] professional [[Boxing|boxer]] and a former [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[List of strawweight boxing champions|Minimumweight World Champion]].\n* [[Jose Dalisay, Jr.]], writer, poet, playwright and screenwriter who won 16 [[Palanca Awards]]\n* [[Gabriel Fabella]], co-founder and first president of the [[Philippine Historical Association]]; Father of [[Philippine Independence Day|June 12 Independence Day]]; and sole representative of Romblon in the First National Assembly (1935\u20131938).\n* [[Ephraim Fajutagana]], former Obispo M\u00e1ximo or Supreme Bishop of the [[Philippine Independent Church]].\n* [[Roilo Golez]], former member of the [[Philippine House of Representatives]] representing the [[Legislative districts of Para\u00f1aque City#2nd District|Second District]] of [[Para\u00f1aque City]].\n* [[N. V. M. Gonzalez]], writer, [[Palanca Award]] winner, and [[Philippine National Artist|National Artist for Literature]].\n* [[Elma Muros|Elma Muros-Posadas]], former [[track and field]] athlete who specialized in [[long jump]] and won a total of 15 gold medals in several [[Southeast Asian Games]].\n* [[Rodne Galicha]], environmentalist, 2018 Ten Outsnading Young Men (TOYM) awardee and recipient of national individual award called Gawad Bayani Kalikasan given by the Center for Environmental Concerns and [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]], former Philippine country manager of [[The Climate Reality Project]].\n* [[Jansen Rios]], Filipino professional basketball player for the [[NLEX Road Warriors]] of the [[Philippine Basketball Association]] (PBA).\n* [[Nene Tamayo]], grand winner of [[ABS-CBN|ABS-CBN's]] ''[[Pinoy Big Brother (season 1)]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{GeoGroup}}\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130320113233/http://www.romblonprov.gov.ph/ Official Website] of the Romblon Provincial Government \n* {{OSM relation|1506343}}\n* [http://www.blgs.gov.ph/lgpmsv2/cmshome/index.php?pageID=23&frmIdDcfCode=7&fLguType=P&frmIdRegion=7&frmIdProvince=&frmIdLgu=43 Local Governance Performance Management System]\n* {{cite journal|url=https://asj.upd.edu.ph/mediabox/archive/ASJ-50-2-2014/Making-Philippine-Provice-Romblon-American-Period-Asian-Studies.pdf|title=The Making of a Philippine Province: Romblon During the American Colonial Period|journal=Asian Studies: Journal of Critical Perspectives on Asia|volume=50|issue=2|pages=74-106|year=2014|first=Kristoffer|last=Esquejo|institution=[[University of the Philippines Diliman]]}}\n{{Geographic location\n| Centre = Romblon\n| North  = [[Marinduque]]<br />''[[Sibuyan Sea]]''\n| East   = {{nowrap|''[[Sibuyan Sea]]'' / [[Masbate]]}}\n| South  = ''[[Sibuyan Sea]]''<br />[[Aklan]]\n| West   = {{nowrap|[[Oriental Mindoro]] / ''[[Tablas Strait]]''}}\n}}\n\n{{Romblon|state=expanded}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Articles related to Romblon\n| list1 =\n{{MIMAROPA}}\n{{Luzon lateral}}\n{{Philippines topics}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Romblon| ]]\n[[Category:Provinces of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Islands of Luzon]]\n[[Category:Island provinces of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Sibuyan Sea]]\n[[Category:Mimaropa]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1917]]\n[[Category:1917 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Luzon]]\n", "name_user": "Aldrin Orlanes Politico", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Romblon"}
{"title_page": "Goran Dragi\u0107", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name = Goran Dragi\u0107\n| image = EuroBasket 2017 Finland vs Slovenia 37 (Goran Dragi\u0107 cropped 2).jpg\n| caption = Dragi\u0107 with Slovenia in 2017\n| alt = \n| position = [[Point guard]] / [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 190\n| league = [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]\n| team = Miami Heat\n| number = 7\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1986|5|6}}\n| birth_place = [[Ljubljana]], [[SR Slovenia]], [[SFR Yugoslavia|Yugoslavia]]\n| nationality = Slovenian\n| draft_year = 2008\n| draft_round = 2\n| draft_pick = 45\n| draft_team = [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| career_start = 2003\n| career_end =\n| years1 = 2003\u20132004\n| team1 = [[KD Ilirija|Ilirija]]\n| years2 = 2004\u20132006\n| team2 = [[KD Slovan|Geoplin Slovan]]\n| years3 = 2006\u20132007\n| team3 = [[CB Murcia|Murcia]]\n| years4 = 2007\u20132008\n| team4 = [[KK Olimpija|Union Olimpija]]\n| years5 = {{nbay|2008|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2010|end}}\n| team5 = [[Phoenix Suns]]\n| years6 = {{nbay|2010|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2011|end}}\n| team6 = [[Houston Rockets]]\n| years7 = 2011\n| team7 = [[Saski Baskonia]]\n| years8 = {{nbay|2012|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2014|end}}\n| team8 = Phoenix Suns\n| years9 = {{nbay|2014|end}}\u2013present\n| team9 = [[Miami Heat]]\n| highlights =\n*[[List of NBA All-Stars|NBA All-Star]] ({{nasg|2018}})\n*[[All-NBA Team|All-NBA Third Team]] ({{nbay|2013|end}})\n*[[NBA Most Improved Player Award|NBA Most Improved Player]] ({{nbay|2013|end}})\n*[[FIBA EuroBasket MVP]] ([[EuroBasket 2017|2017]])\n*[[FIBA Stankovi\u0107 Cup]] MVP ([[2010 FIBA Stankovi\u0107 Continental Champions' Cup|2010]])\n*[[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian League]] champion (2008)\n*Slovenian League All-Star (2006)\n*Slovenian League Rookie of the Year (2005)\n*[[Slovenian Sportsman of the year]] (2017)\n| profile = goran_dragic\n| bbr = dragigo01\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{bk|SLO}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA EuroBasket]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[EuroBasket 2017|2017 Turkey]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2004 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship|2004 Brno]]|[[Slovenia men's national under-20 basketball team|Under-20 Team]]}}\n}}\n'''Goran Dragi\u0107''' (born 6 May 1986) is a Slovenian professional [[basketball]] player for the [[Miami Heat]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). He plays at both the [[point guard]] and [[shooting guard]] positions. He played professional basketball in Slovenia and Spain before entering the NBA in 2008.<ref name=SeptemberSign>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/news/sign_dragic_080825.html |title=Suns Sign Goran Dragic &#124; The Official Site Of The Phoenix Suns |publisher=Nba.com |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> Dragi\u0107 has played for the [[Phoenix Suns]] twice, the [[Houston Rockets]], and the Heat. He was an [[All-NBA Third Team]] selection and the [[NBA Most Improved Player Award|NBA Most Improved Player]] with the Suns in 2014. He was named an [[NBA All-Star]] for the first time in 2018 with Miami. He led the senior [[Slovenian national basketball team|Slovenian national team]] to its first [[FIBA EuroBasket]] title in [[EuroBasket 2017|2017]], while being named the [[FIBA EuroBasket MVP|Most Valuable Player of the tournament]].\n\n==Professional career==\n===Europe===\nDragi\u0107 began his professional career in 2003, at the age of 17, in the [[Slovenian Second Basketball League]] with [[KD Ilirija]]. He played there for one year, before transferring to the top level [[Premier A Slovenian Basketball League|Slovenian Basketball League]] and [[NLB League|Adriatic League]] club [[KD Slovan|Slovan]], in 2004. After spending two years with Slovan, he transferred to the [[Liga ACB|Spanish ACB League]] club [[Saski Baskonia]], who [[loan (sports)|loaned]] him to the Spanish club club [[CB Murcia|Murcia]], in 2006.\n\nDragi\u0107 joined the Slovenian club [[KK Union Olimpija|Union Olimpija]] in 2007, and he played there during the 2007\u201308 season, winning the Slovenian League championship with the team.\n\n===NBA===\n====Phoenix Suns (2008\u20132011)====\nDragi\u0107 entered the [[2008 NBA draft]], where he was selected in the second round, 45th overall, by the [[San Antonio Spurs]]. His draft rights were then traded to the [[Phoenix Suns]] in exchange for the draft rights to [[Malik Hairston]], the 48th pick.  After the Suns finished a deal with [[Saski Baskonia|TAU Ceramica]] (now known as Caja Laboral), with whom he was under contract, they officially signed him on 22 September 2008.<ref name=SeptemberSign/> The Suns hoped that he would take over the starting point guard position after [[Steve Nash]] relinquished it.<ref name=SeptemberSign/><ref name=DecemberArticle12>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/2008/12/11/20081211sunsdebut1212.html |title=New suns may play tonight |publisher=Azcentral.com |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> On 25 January 2010, Dragi\u0107 scored a then career high 32 points, hitting 6 of 7 three-pointers in a losing effort against the Utah Jazz.<ref>{{cite web|author=Loren Jorgensen |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705361116/Utah-Jazz-Little-known-Dragic-enjoys-career-night-for-Suns.html |title=Utah Jazz: Little-known Dragic enjoys career night for Suns |publisher=Deseret News |date=26 January 2010 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 May 2010, during [[2010 NBA Playoffs#(3) Phoenix Suns vs. (7) San Antonio Spurs|game 3 of the Western Conference Semifinals]], he led a Phoenix Suns comeback against the team that originally drafted him, the San Antonio Spurs, scoring 23 of his total 26 points in the fourth quarter. Dragi\u0107 scored his points on 10/13 FG attempts including 5/5 three-pointers and a 4-point play, as the Suns overcame an early 18-point deficit to defeat the Spurs 110\u201396 and take a 3\u20130 lead in their best of seven series in the Western Conference Semifinals. \"I think it's safe to say that may have been the best fourth-quarter performance I have ever seen in a playoff game\", Suns forward [[Grant Hill]] said.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=300507024 |title=Phoenix Suns vs. San Antonio Spurs - Recap - May 07, 2010 - ESPN |publisher=Scores.espn.go.com |date=7 May 2010 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Houston Rockets (2011\u20132012)====\nOn 24 February 2011, Dragi\u0107 was traded to the [[Houston Rockets]] along with a protected first-round pick in exchange for [[Aaron Brooks (basketball)|Aaron Brooks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azcentral.com/sports/suns/articles/2011/02/24/20110224phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-aaron-brooks-houston-rockets-nba-trade.html |title=Phoenix Suns trade Goran Dragic for Aaron Brooks from Houston Rockets |publisher=azcentral.com |date= |accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chron.com/sports/rockets/article/Rockets-trade-Battier-Brooks-in-separate-deals-1549128.php |title=Rockets trade Battier, Brooks in separate deals |work=Houston Chronicle |date= |accessdate=25 August 2011}}</ref> On 13 April 2011, in the Rockets' season finale, Dragi\u0107 recorded his first career triple-double with 11 points, 11 assists and 11 rebounds in a 121\u2013102 win over the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=310413016|title=Rockets send Timberwolves to 15th straight loss|work=ESPN.com|date=13 April 2011|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2011 NBA lockout]], he played for [[Saski Baskonia]] of Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroleague.net/euroleaguenews/transactions/2011-12-signings/i/89886/5611/caja-laboral-tabs-guard-dragic |title=CAJA LABORAL tabs guard Dragic - 2011-12 SIGNINGS - Welcome to EUROLEAGUE BASKETBALL |publisher=Euroleague.net |date=20 November 2011 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> He played for a brief period of time there until the lockout ended. He returned to the Rockets for the 2011\u201312 season. Throughout most of the season, Dragi\u0107 continued to be used as a bench player as a means to help the Rockets out during the lockout shortened season. In March 2012, he filled in for [[Kyle Lowry]], who was out with a bacterial infection. On 9 April 2012, Dragi\u0107 won the Western Conference Player of the Week.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/09/players-of-the-week-lebron-james-goran-dragic/ |title=Rockets' Dragic, Heat's James named Players of the Week |publisher=NBA.com |date=9 April 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309150917/http://www.nba.com/2012/news/04/09/players-of-the-week-lebron-james-goran-dragic/ |archivedate=9 March 2014  }}</ref>\n\n====Second stint with the Suns (2012\u20132015)====\nIn 2012, Dragi\u0107 became an unrestricted free agent. He agreed to sign a 4-year, $30 million deal with a player option on the final year with the [[Phoenix Suns]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spotrac.com/nba/phoenix-suns/goran-dragic/ |title=Goran Dragic Salary Cap, Contracts, Salaries, Cap Hits, & News Profile |publisher=Spotrac.com |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> and officially became a member of the team again on 19 July 2012. He was brought in to replace [[Steve Nash]], whom he played behind during his first stint with the Suns, as starting point guard. On 19 February 2013, Dragi\u0107 recorded a career-high 18 assists to go with 14 points as the Suns defeated the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] 102\u201398. Dragi\u0107 nearly recorded a [[triple-double]] against the [[Brooklyn Nets]] with 31 points, 12 assists, and 9 rebounds on 24 March 2013. Despite suffering through a 25\u201357 season, Dragi\u0107 ended up gaining some career high moments in the process.\n\nAfter getting [[Eric Bledsoe]] from a trade with the [[Los Angeles Clippers]], the Suns ultimately decided to move Dragi\u0107 to the shooting guard position as a means of putting less pressure on Dragi\u0107 to distribute the ball to his teammates. In his first game playing with Bledsoe as a teammate, Dragi\u0107 led the team with 26 points and 9 assists in a 104\u201391 season opening victory over the [[Portland Trail Blazers]]. Dragi\u0107 had over 8 games with 30 points or more, including a double-double of 31 points and 10 assists in a victory against the Portland Trail Blazers on 27 November 2013. He also had what was, at the time, a career-high 33 points in a loss to the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] on 2 January 2014. On 3 February 2014, Dragi\u0107 won his second career Western Conference Player of the Week award and his first with the Suns for games played between 27 January \u2013 2 February 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/02/03/lowry-dragic-named-players-of-week/index.html |title=Lowry, Dragic named Players of the Week |publisher=NBA.com |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204162228/http://www.nba.com/2014/news/02/03/lowry-dragic-named-players-of-week/index.html |archive-date=4 February 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Three days later, he was paired with [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] guard [[Reggie Jackson (basketball, born 1990)|Reggie Jackson]] in the revamped, team-based Skills Challenge at the All-Star weekend\n\nOn 8 February 2014, Dragi\u0107 scored a career-high 34 points\u2014 while attempting only 13 field-goals\u2014 to go along with 10 assists in a 122\u2013109 home victory over the [[Golden State Warriors]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20140208/GSWPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Notebook: Suns 122, Warriors 109 |work=NBA.com |date=8 February 2014 |accessdate=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180518132219/http://www.nba.com/games/20140208/GSWPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=18 May 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On 23 February 2014, Dragi\u0107 scored a new career-high 35 points, along with 3 assists and 3 steals, in a 112\u2013115 loss to the Houston Rockets.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20140223/HOUPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Notebook: Rockets 115, Suns 112 |access-date=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526135405/https://www.nba.com/games/20140223/HOUPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=26 May 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|7jVMxL7-YPk|Goran Dragic Scores a Career-High 35 Points}}</ref> On 28 February 2014, he recorded a new career-high 40 points, along with 3 rebounds and 5 assists, in a 116\u2013104 win over the [[New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20140228/NOPPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Notebook: Suns 116, Pelicans 104 |access-date=1 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190526140935/https://www.nba.com/games/20140228/NOPPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=26 May 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{YouTube|Kp7ZqDY6vPg|Goran Dragic Scores a Career High... for the Second Time This Week!}}</ref> He became the first player, since [[Rod Strickland]] in 1985\u201386, to set career highs in points three times in a single month. Dragi\u0107 also became the sixth player, after his head coach [[Jeff Hornacek]], [[Dra\u017een Petrovi\u0107]], [[Dirk Nowitzki]], [[LeBron James]], and [[Kevin Durant]], to join the 20-50-40 Club \u2014 averaging 20 or more points per game while shooting 50%+ from the field and 40%+ on three-pointers.<ref>http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2014/4/7/5588628/phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-about-to-join-exclusive-20-50-40-club</ref><ref>http://valleyofthesuns.com/2014/04/16/goran-dragic-joins-hornacek-petrovic-on-exclusive-list/</ref> He also averaged over 5 assists per game throughout the season as well, leaving him joining the likes of [[Larry Bird]], [[Jeff Hornacek]] and [[LeBron James]].<ref>http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2014/4/23/5643752/phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-named-nbas-most-improved-player-for-2013-14</ref><ref>http://www.brightsideofthesun.com/2014/6/4/5779748/phoenix-suns-goran-dragic-named-to-2013-14-all-nba-third-team</ref>\n\nOn 23 April 2014, Dragi\u0107 won the 2014 [[NBA Most Improved Player Award]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/04/23/goran-dragic-wins-kia-most-improved-player-award/ |title=Suns' Dragic wins Kia Most Improved Player award |access-date=23 April 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180128094023/http://www.nba.com/2014/news/04/23/goran-dragic-wins-kia-most-improved-player-award/ |archive-date=28 January 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref> One month later, he would end up being honored by his home nation with their national \"Apple of Inspiration\" award for being a role model and inspiring hope in Slovenia, as well as helping out the nation's community with humanitarian activities.<ref>[http://www.sta.si/en/vest.php?s=a&id=2012201 Basketball Player Dragi\u0107 Honoured by President Pahor]</ref> Finally, on 4 June 2014, Dragi\u0107 was named to the 2014 [[All-NBA team|All-NBA third team]] alongside [[Damian Lillard]], [[LaMarcus Aldridge]], [[Al Jefferson]] and [[Paul George]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/06/04/2013-14-all-nba-teams/ |title=Durant, LeBron headline 2013-14 All-NBA First Team |access-date=4 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140604220936/http://www.nba.com/2014/news/06/04/2013-14-all-nba-teams/ |archive-date=4 June 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Miami Heat (2015\u2013present)====\n[[File:Goran Dragic (30303474504).jpg|thumb|Dragi\u0107 with the Heat in 2016.]]\nOn 19 February 2015, Dragi\u0107 and his brother, Zoran, were traded to the [[Miami Heat]] in a three-team deal also involving the [[New Orleans Pelicans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/heat-acquire-goran-dragic-and-zoran-dragic|title=HEAT Acquire Goran Dragic and Zoran Dragic|date=19 February 2015|work=NBA.com|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> Two days later, he made his debut for the Heat, recording 12 points and 3 rebounds in a 105\u201391 loss to the New Orleans Pelicans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150221/NOPMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223235430/http://www.nba.com/games/20150221/NOPMIA/gameinfo.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 February 2015|title=Pelicans lose Davis and Anderson, roll past Heat 105-91|date=21 February 2015|work=NBA.com|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> Dragi\u0107 finished the season averaging 16.6 points and 5.3 assists per game in 26 starts for Miami, as the Heat missed the playoffs.\n\nOn 9 July 2015, Dragi\u0107 re-signed with the Heat to a five-year, $90 million contract.<ref>{{cite news|title=HEAT Re-Signs Goran Dragic|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/heat-re-signs-goran-dragic|accessdate=13 July 2015|work=NBA.com|date=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Stein | first = Marc | title = Goran Dragic, Miami Heat agree to five-year, $90 million deal | url = http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/13179887/goran-dragic-miami-heat-reach-agreement-five-year-90-million-deal | work = ESPN.com | date = 1 July 2015 | accessdate = 1 July 2015}}</ref> In January 2016, he missed eight straight games because of a left calf injury.<ref>{{cite web | last = Braun | first = Rick | title = Miami Heat guard Goran Dragic likely to return Friday night vs. Bucks | url = http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/nba/miami-heat/article57195813.html | work = MiamiHerald.com | date = 28 January 2016 | accessdate = 30 January 2016}}</ref> On 20 February 2016, he recorded a season-high 24 points, eight assists and seven rebounds in a 114\u201384 win over the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Whiteside has 25 points, 23 rebounds; Heat beat Wizards|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160220/WASMIA/gameinfo.html|accessdate=21 February 2016|work=NBA.com|date=20 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170209230443/http://www.nba.com/games/20160220/WASMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-date=9 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> He bested that season high on 11 March, recording 26 points and nine assists in a 118\u201396 win over the [[Chicago Bulls]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dragic scores 26 as Heat beat Bulls 118-96|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160311/MIACHI/gameinfo.html|accessdate=11 March 2016|work=NBA.com|date=11 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108011007/http://www.nba.com/games/20160311/MIACHI/gameinfo.html|archive-date=8 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 7 April, he recorded 16 points and a career-high 12 rebounds in a 106\u201398 win over the Chicago Bulls, helping the Heat sweep the season series with the Bulls for the first time since the 2003\u201304 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Heat rally past Bulls, 106-98 for 46th win of the season|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160407/CHIMIA/gameinfo.html|accessdate=7 April 2016|work=NBA.com|date=7 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124735/http://www.nba.com/games/20160407/CHIMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-date=9 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the Heat's second-round playoff match-up with the Toronto Raptors, Dragi\u0107 scored a postseason career-high 30 points to help the Heat to a 103\u201391 victory in Game 6, tying the series at 3\u20133.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dragic, Wade lead Heat past Raptors 103-91 _ and into Game 7|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20160513/TORMIA/gameinfo.html|accessdate=14 May 2016|work=NBA.com|date=13 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124900/http://www.nba.com/games/20160513/TORMIA/gameinfo.html|archive-date=9 December 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Heat went on to lose Game 7, bowing out of the playoffs with a 4\u20133 defeat.\n\nOn 28 November 2016, Dragi\u0107 recorded season highs of 27 points and 17 assists in a 112\u2013104 loss to the Boston Celtics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899706|title=Thomas scores 25, Celtics get past Heat 112-104|work=ESPN.com|date=28 November 2016|accessdate=29 November 2016}}</ref> He topped that mark on 6 December 2016, scoring 29 points (his highest-scoring total as a member of the Heat at the time) in a 114\u2013103 loss to the [[New York Knicks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899758|title=Anthony scores 35, Knicks beat depleted Heat 114-103|work=ESPN.com|date=6 December 2016|accessdate=6 December 2016}}</ref> Dragi\u0107 set a new season high six days later, scoring 34 points in a 112\u2013101 win over the [[Washington Wizards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400899805|title=Dragic scores 34, Heat beat Wizards 112-101 to snap slide|work=ESPN.com|date=12 December 2016|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> On 6 February 2017, he scored 33 points and hit a career-high seven three-pointers to lead the Heat to their 11th straight victory with a 115\u2013113 win over the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400900180|title=Dragic leads Heat to 11th straight win, 115-113 over Wolves|work=ESPN.com|date=6 February 2017|accessdate=7 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 November 2017, Dragi\u0107 scored a season-high 29 points in a 126\u2013115 win over the Phoenix Suns.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=400974913|title=Goran Dragic scores season-high 29, Heat beat Suns 126-115|work=ESPN.com|date=8 November 2017|accessdate=8 November 2017}}</ref> On 27 November 2017, he was named the Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played Monday, 20 November through Sunday, 26 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/goran-dragic-named-eastern-conference-player-week|title=Goran Dragic Named Eastern Conference Player of the Week|work=NBA.com|date=27 November 2017|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> On 15 January 2018, he was named the Eastern Conference Player of the Week for games played Monday, 8 January through Sunday, 14 January. It was his fourth career Player of the Week honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/news/goran-dragic-named-eastern-conference-player-week-0|title=Goran Dragi\u0107 Named Eastern Conference Player Of The Week|work=NBA.com|date=15 January 2018|accessdate=15 January 2018}}</ref> On 1 February, Dragi\u0107 was named the replacement for [[Kevin Love]] on Team [[LeBron James|LeBron]] for the [[2018 NBA All-Star Game]], thus making him an All-Star for the first time in his career.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dragic Selected to 2018 NBA All-Star Team|url=http://www.nba.com/heat/dragic-selected-to-2018-nba-all-star-team|accessdate=1 February 2018|work=NBA.com|date=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 2018, Dragi\u0107 scored 28 points in a 120\u2013111 win over the [[Portland Trail Blazers]], becoming the first [[Slovenia]]n player to reach the 10,000-point mark in the NBA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401070760|title=Dragic scores 28, Heat outlast Trail Blazers 120-111|work=ESPN.com|date=27 October 2018|accessdate=27 October 2018}}</ref> In late November and early December, he missed eight games with a sore right knee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071057|title=Adebayo's career-high 22 points helps Heat beat Suns 115-98|work=ESPN.com|date=7 December 2018|accessdate=8 December 2018}}</ref> On 19 December, he underwent successful surgery to clean up his right knee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/heat/news/goran-dragic-undergoes-surgery-181219|title=Goran Dragi\u0107 Undergoes Surgery|work=NBA.com|date=19 December 2018|accessdate=19 December 2018}}</ref> He returned to action on 23 February 2019 against the [[Detroit Pistons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071561|title=Pistons reach 7th in East, top reeling Heat 119-96|work=ESPN.com|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=24 February 2018|quote=Miami got point guard Goran Dragic on the floor for the first time since Dec. 10, after a two-month rehab to recover from right knee surgery.}}</ref> On 28 March, he recorded his second career triple-double with 23 points, 12 rebounds and 11 assists in a 105\u201399 win over the [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/recap?gameId=401071797|title=Dragic's triple-double lifts Heat past Mavs, 105-99|work=ESPN.com|date=28 March 2019|accessdate=29 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\n===Slovenian junior national team===\nDragi\u0107 won the gold medal at the [[2004 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]] with the [[Slovenia men's national under-20 basketball team|Slovenian under-20 junior national team]]. He also played at the [[2005 FIBA Europe Under-20 Championship]].\n\n===Slovenian senior national team===\n[[File:Slovenia vs. Serbia at EuroBasket 2009 (36).jpg|thumb|Dragi\u0107 playing with [[Slovenian national basketball team|Slovenia]] at the [[2009 EuroBasket]]]]\nDragi\u0107 competed with the senior men's [[Slovenia national basketball team|Slovenian national basketball team]] at the [[2006 FIBA World Championship]] and the [[2007 EuroBasket]], in limited roles. Dragi\u0107's role with the Slovenian national basketball team began to increase in the [[2009 EuroBasket]] and the [[2010 FIBA World Championship]]. He then played with his brother [[Zoran Dragi\u0107|Zoran]] in the [[2011 EuroBasket]] and the [[2013 EuroBasket]], the latter which was held in [[Slovenia]]. During the 2013 tournament, Goran and his brother helped lead Slovenia to a 5th-place finish and a spot in the [[2014 FIBA World Cup]]. Dragi\u0107 finished in the 2013 EuroBasket's top five in points and assists, which earned him a spot on the [[EuroBasket All-Tournament Team|All-Tournament Team]]. In 2014, Dragi\u0107 was named Slovenia's [[captain (sports)|team captain]] after [[Jaka Lakovi\u010d]] retired from [[national sports team|national team]] play. In the [[friendly game]]s before the [[2014 FIBA World Cup]], Dragi\u0107 was rested in 9 of their 14 games, before actually playing in the official tournament's matches. After finishing up their friendly games, Dragi\u0107 played with no restrictions beyond the rest of the competition; he was the only [[All-NBA Team]] member to play in the 2014 FIBA World Cup, aside from the [[2014 United States FIBA Basketball World Cup team|Team USA]] members.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nPrior to the [[2017 EuroBasket]], Dragi\u0107 announced that he would retire from playing with the Slovenian national team after the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-heat/fl-sp-miami-heat-goran-dragic-s20170829-story.html |title=Miami Heat guard Goran Dragic to retire from international play after EuroBasket |first=Ira |last=Winderman |newspaper=[[Sun-Sentinel]] |location=[[Deerfield Beach, Florida]] |date=29 August 2017 |accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref> At the tournament, he helped Slovenia to win its first ever FIBA European championship. He scored 35 points, on 12-22 shooting in the [[EuroBasket 2017 Final|final]], which was the most points scored in a final, since [[Pau Gasol]] scored 36 points in the [[EuroBasket 2003|2003]] final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heatzone.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2017/09/17/goran-dragic-leads-slovenia-to-eurobasket-gold-with-35-points-named-mvp-of-tournament/|title=Goran Dragic leads Slovenia to EuroBasket gold with 35 points - Heat Zone|publisher=|accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> Following his performance, Dragi\u0107 was given the [[FIBA EuroBasket MVP|Most Valuable Player award of the tournament]], after averaging 22.6 points per game, in 9 games played.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/news/title-hero-dragic-caps-off-fairy-tale-finish-with-mvp-honors|title=Title hero Dragic caps off fairy tale finish with MVP honors|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=19 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=MVP>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/eurobasket/2017/news/title-hero-dragic-caps-off-fairy-tale-finish-with-mvp-honors|title=Title hero Dragic caps off fairy tale finish with MVP honors|publisher=fiba.basketball|date=17 September 2017}}</ref> Following that performance, he was named the 2017 [[Slovenian Sportsman of the year]].\n\n==Personal life==\nDragi\u0107 was born to a Slovenian mother and a Serbian father.<ref>[http://www.downtownphoenixjournal.com/2010/02/04/suns-spot-el-dragon/]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302192458/http://www.downtownphoenixjournal.com/2010/02/04/suns-spot-el-dragon/|date=2 March 2010}}</ref> He grew up in Slovenia playing [[Association football|football]]. However, an injury forced him to switch sports. As a child, he admired NBA players [[Michael Jordan]], [[Allen Iverson]] and former teammate [[Steve Nash]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/goran_dragic/bio.html|title=Goran Dragic Stats, Video, Bio, Profile|publisher=NBA.com|accessdate=1 March 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025071832/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/goran_dragic/bio.html|archivedate=25 October 2013}}</ref> He is fluent in [[Slovene language|Slovenian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]], Spanish, and English.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://nba.us/playerfile/goran_dragic/bio.html |title=Goran Dragic Stats, Video, Bio, Profile &#124; NBA.com |publisher=Nba.us |date= |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> Dragi\u0107's younger brother, [[Zoran Dragi\u0107|Zoran]], was formerly his teammate on the Phoenix Suns and Miami Heat,<ref>{{cite news|title=Suns Sign Zoran Dragi\u0107|url=http://www.nba.com/suns/press-release/suns-sign-zoran-dragic|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=30 September 2014|work=NBA.com}}</ref> and currently plays in Germany for [[ratiopharm Ulm]].<ref>{{cite news|title=EA7 Milan inks Dragic at guard|url=http://www.euroleague.net/news/i/746egud9j589imq6/ea7-milan-inks-dragic-at-guard|accessdate=16 July 2016|work=Euroleague.net|date=7 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Dragi\u0107 married his long-time girlfriend, Maja.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.delo.si/sport/eurobasket/dragic-vzel-le-en-prost-dan-da-se-je-ozenil.html |title=Dragi\u0107 vzel le en prost dan, da se je o\u017eenil |publisher=Delo.si |date=23 August 2013 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.siol.net/sportal/kosarka/ep2013/novice/2013/08/sloveniji_bo_zdaj_poveljeval_poroceni_dragic.aspx |title=Sloveniji bo zdaj poveljeval poro\u010deni Dragi\u0107 &#124; EP 2013 - Planet |publisher=Siol.net |date=22 August 2013 |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref> In November 2013, Dragi\u0107's first son, Mateo, was born.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://valleyofthesuns.com/2013/11/11/defense-has-helped-the-suns-become-the-nbas-surprise-team/ |title=Defense has helped the Suns become the NBA's surprise team |publisher=Valleyofthesuns.com |accessdate=1 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe and Zoran, alongside teammates [[Markieff Morris|Markieff]] and [[Marcus Morris (basketball)|Marcus Morris]], all briefly played together for the Suns during the fourth quarter of their 112\u201396 victory over the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] on 2 January 2015. It marked the first time in the NBA's history that two different pairs of brothers played together for the same team at the same time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150102/PHIPHX/gameinfo.html |title=Green helps Suns pull away from 76ers, 112-96 |access-date=9 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170901084149/http://www.nba.com/games/20150102/PHIPHX/gameinfo.html |archive-date=1 September 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[[President of Republika Srpska]] [[Milorad Dodik]] honored Dragi\u0107 with an Order of Njego\u0161 and a Medal of Merit for the People, in August 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Goran Dragi\u0107 posetio Igokeu, Dodik ga odlikovao Njego\u0161evim ordenom |url=https://www.b92.net/sport/kosarka/vesti.php?yyyy=2018&mm=08&dd=15&nav_id=1431133 |website=b92.net |accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nDragi\u0107 is an [[Serbian Orthodox Church|Eastern Orthodox Christian]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Sem Slovenec , pravoslavne vere. Na dana\u0161nji praznik ti \u017eelim, mir v du\u0161i in radost v srcu. |url=https://twitter.com/Goran_Dragic/status/1082307839467708416 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u041c\u0418\u0420 \u0411\u041e\u0416\u0418\u0408\u0418, \u0425\u0420\u0418\u0421\u0422\u041e\u0421 \u0421\u0415 \u0420\u041e\u0414\u0418! |url=https://twitter.com/reno_968/status/1082306420123545600 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=7 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2008}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2008\u201309 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 55 || 1 || 13.2 || .393 || .370 || .769 || 1.9 || 2.0 || .5 || .1 || 4.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2009}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2009\u201310 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| '''80''' || 2 || 18.0 || .452 || .394 || .736 || 2.1 || 3.0 || .6 || .1 || 7.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2010}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2010\u201311 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 48 || 2 || 17.8 || .421 || .277 || .608 || 1.8 || 3.1 || .8 || .1 || 7.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2010}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2010\u201311 Houston Rockets season|Houston]]\n| 22 || 3 || 17.2 || .472 || '''.519''' || .667 || 2.5 || 2.5 || .6 || .2 || 7.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2011}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2011\u201312 Houston Rockets season|Houston]]\n| 66 || 28 || 26.5 || .462 || .337 || .805 || 2.5 || 5.3 || 1.3 || .2 || 11.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2012}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2012\u201313 Phoenix Suns season|Phoenix]]\n| 77 || '''77''' || 33.5 || .443 || .319 || .748 || 3.1 || '''7.4''' || '''1.6''' || '''.3''' || 14